<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Become Modern Farmers Because of Institutional Reform (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiangxi's provincial governor, Shu Shengyou, said his province
is an agricultural province with little science and technology and
few social services. With its large amount of of barren hillsides
and uncultivated land, he added, it has great agricultural
potential.
</P>
<P>
They intend to adopt a series of preferential policies to
prompt more officials to go to rural areas where they can do
something really significant, he says.
</P>
<P>
Various media report that, in other provinces, the agricultural
sector has become a destination of government officials or workers
laid off by state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to some statistics, about 30 percent of China's 33
million hectares of barren hills have now been cultivated, and a
large number of the people involved are former officials and
workers from the cities.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China's state-owned sector had laid off
about 11 million people and the number is expected to increase by
3.5 million this year.
</P>
<P>
Many people believe that it's a good idea to encourage
officials and unemployed workers, who are better-educated and more
open-minded than most farmers, to go to rural backward areas and
start operating farms in a more modern way.
</P>
<P>
This could help change the old ways where rural areas seriously
lacked skilled personnel with modern management techniques and
could be one way of guaranteeing the modernization of China's
agriculture, according to Zhu Mei'e, a professor of economics at
the Jiangxi Finance and Economics College.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
