<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 16:00 GMT March 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin reiterated Monday
that he would not run for the 2000 presidential elections, but he
did not name sacked Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as his
successor.
</P>
<P>
"In our country people elect leaders, and every citizen has the
right to run for presidency under the constitution," Yeltsin
said. (Russia-Yeltsin-Chernomyrdin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Oil prices of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) rose dramatically on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The price of OPEC's basket of seven crudes climbed to 13.20
U.S. dollars a barrel from 11.22 dollars a week ago, the
secretariat of the leading international oil group
said. (OPEC-Oil-Price)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak held talks on Monday
with the United States Mideast envoy Dennis Ross on ways of
breaking deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
They reviewed the latest situations in the region in the light
of Ross' talks with Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
(Egypt-Ross-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Iraq Monday threatened a trade boycott of
Australian wheat and dairy exports unless Australia withdraws its
nearly 200 servicemen in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The boycott could block Australian access to a planned 198
million U.S. dollar expansion of Iraq's dairy market and 132
million dollars in annual wheat imports under the Oil-for-Food
program. (Australia-Iraq-Boycott) 
</P>
</TEXT>
