<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Launch NILESAT in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's first satellite, NILESAT,
will be launched into orbit on April 28 from South America, the
Middle East News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be placed in a launching position on the
French rocket Ariane 4 on April 14 before final tests are carried
out on April 24 for launching, Information Minister Safwat Al
Sherif said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will be the first country in the area to launch its own
satellite, according to the information minister.
</P>
<P>
"From that moment, Egypt will enter the space age and becomes
the 60th member in the world space club," Sherif said in an
interview with the Egyptian news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian satellite was transported on March 23 from the
place of its manufacture and assembly at Tolouse, southwest
France, to Guyana, after a trans-Atlantic nine-hour journey, by a
giant Russian-made Antinov plane.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, NILESAT will combine 12 channels,
with each airing six programs simultaneously through digital
technology. Some channels will specialize in news coverage, women,
drama and music.
</P>
<P>
Ground facilities necessary for the operation of the NILESAT
have been completed at the October 6 City, in southern Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's first satellite is run by an Egyptian stock company to
which the Egyptian Radio and TV Union has a 40 percent stake, the
banking industry 15 percent, private enterprises 25 percent and
the public holding 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 158-million-dollar project is expected to rake in huge
profits to cover the costs in a span of four to five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
