<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 65 Taliban Prisoners Released by Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Former Afghanistan's military
chief Ahmad Masood, one of the leaders of the anti-Taliban
alliance, released 65 Taliban prisoners Monday, a report by the
Associated Press of Pakistan said.
</P>
<P>
The release ceremony held in Panjsher Valley, about 120
kilometers north of Kabul, was attended by officials from the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), the report said,
adding that the ICRC will help transport the freed men to the
Taliban-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
The release came a day after the Taliban leader, Mulla Mohammad
Omar, ordered his followers not to kill any opposition soldier
held by them, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that a total of 7,000 prisoners are held by the
Taliban and the anti-Taliban northern alliance, out of which about
1,200 are in custody of Masood, the report said.
</P>
<P>
About two months ago, the Taliban militia, who control two
thirds of Afghanistan including the capital of Kabul, released
around 200 prisoners after the northern alliance freed almost an
equal number of their prisoners in December, last year.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance, composed of forces led by
ethnic-Uzbek warlord Rashid Dostum, the Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat and
Masood, has been battling the Taliban since the militia drove them
out from Kabul in September, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
