<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Climb to Record High in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide new home
sales shot up to a record high in February, thanks to low mortgage
rates and unseasonably warm weather, the Commerce Department
reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sales of new single-family homes surged 4.8 percent to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 893,000, as against the old
record of 880,000 set in March 1986, the department said.
</P>
<P>
The country's new home sales are off to an extraordinarily fast
start this year as they rose 5.2 percent in January following
hitting a 19-year high of 804,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Realtors reported last week that
existing home sales hit a record 4.75 million annual rate during
the month.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believed that some combined factors have helped the
robust market which include mild temperatures associated with the
El Nino current in the Pacific Ocean, mortgage rates hovering
around a four-year low of 7 percent and healthy growth pushing the
nation's unemployment rate to a 24-year low of 4.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
