<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Syria to Develop Medical, Health Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of Iraq and Syria had
talks here Monday on developing medical and health ties between
the two countries, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks was held between Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat
Mubarak and Syrian Health Minister Iyad Shatti who arrived in
Baghdad on Sunday for a visit, first of its kind since the two
countries broke ties in 1980.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Mubarak expressed the hope that the visit
of the Syrian delegation to participate in the Iraqi-Syrian
Medical Week which started Monday, would enhance bilateral
relations in medical and health fields.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Shatti expressed Syria's appreciation for the
Iraqi people in facing up to the hard conditions caused by the
U.N. embargo against Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, and reiterated
Syria's solidarity with Iraq for putting an end to the suffering
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that we could always meet in service of our common
interests and those of Arab nations in all aspects," said Shatti.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Syrian delegation showed a list of
foodstuffs and medicine presented as a gift from the Syrian
people to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Iraq and Syria were severed in 1980 when Syria
sided with Iran during the eight-year Iraq-Iran war (1980-88). The
relations have further worsened after Syrian troops joined in the
multinational allied forces in the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Iraq began to take measures to resume trade ties
with Syria by buying food and re-opening customs offices on the
border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria opposed to the use of force against Iraq during the
Iraq-U.N. weapons inspection crisis, when the United States and
Britain threatened to launch military strikes against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan is Jordan's First Aid Donor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Japan has given Jordan a total of
235.783 billion yen (about 1.816 billion U.S. dollars) in aid over
the past 20 years, making it the first aid donor for the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
According to Japanese Economic Counselor to Jordan, Mataya
Atanaka, Japan's aid made up 23 percent of the overall
international aid to Jordan over the two decades.
</P>
<P>
The aid took the forms of loans and grants. The total amount of
grants stood at 26.517 billion yen (about 204 million dollars)
from 1979 to 1996, said Atanaka.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of loans from 1974 to 1996, on the other hand,
was 209.266 billion yen (about 1.611 billion dollars). Most of the
loans had a maturity of 30 years, with a grace period of 10 years
and carried annual interest rates ranging from 1 to 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The aid has helped to improve the country's water, irrigation,
environment, energy and communication projects.
</P>
<P>
"Japan thinks we are important to the peace of the region and
therefore to that of the world," Jordan's Deputy Prime Minister
for Services and Minister of Information Affairs Abdullah Ensour
said at a press conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom "deserves it," he said, and it is exploring the
possibility of more Japanese loans and grants to finance the
construction of the King Hussein Bridge linking Jordan and the
West Bank, projects in the fields of regional development, water
and road, and its industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
The United States ranked second in terms of aid for Jordan,
followed by Germany and France. The U.S. provided Jordan 1.552
billion dollars in total from 1990 to 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
