<HEADLINE> Saudi Crown Prince Visits Hamas Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Saudi crown prince Monday
called on Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmad Yassin who is
receiving treatment in Saudi Arabia to show "constant support to
the Palestinian people," reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
When visiting Yassin in King Fahd Hospital in Saudi Red Sea
coastal city of Jeddah, Crown Prince and Deputy Prime Minister
Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz "inquired about the health of Sheikh
Yassin and the health care he is receiving," the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The official Saudi Press Agency said the visit came to express
"constant support to the Palestinian people and the Palestinian
cause by the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia and its leaders in all Arab,
Islamic and international fora."
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Yassin, who suffered from ear problems, arrived in
Jeddah on March 4 after spending more than two weeks in Cairo for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Yassin was released from the Israeli jail in last October. His
release was seen as a move to appease Jordan after Israel's
botched assassination of Hamas (Islamic Resistance Movement) Amman
office leader Khalid Mashaal in Jordan and win freedom of the two
Israeli secret agents who performed the attempt and later were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has constantly called on Israel to abide by the
U.N. Security Council resolutions concerning the Middle East peace
process and expressed its firm support to the Palestinian
people's cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: U.S. Fears Peace Process Near End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The ideas U.S. Mideast Peace
Coordinator Dennis Ross presented to Egypt translate Washington's
concern that the peace process could be drawing to an end,
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the statement after Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak held talks with the U.S. envoy on ways of breaking
deadlock in the Mideast peace process in the Red Sea resort of
Sharm el-Sheikh on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
"If matters do not move forward, then they will move backward,
and this is what these leaders should know," he added, saying that
the U.S. concern for the peace deadlock reflects the truth.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Friday to
American Jewish leaders that the process was not moving forward
and that the region could face danger by 1999 if Israel did not
withdraw from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross briefed Mubarak on the outcome of his talks with the
Palestinian and Israeli leaders on the new U.S. plan to reactivate
the deadlocked peace process, Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But Moussa added he could not say whether the talks Ross held
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat had reached a specific
result.
</P>
<P>
The talks, however, remain ongoing, said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat is expected in Egypt, and therefore we consider the
talks ongoing. One can not say that there is anything new so far,
but, certainly there is some kind of activity that can lead to the
progress we hope for," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ross told Mubarak that he would meet Netanyahu later in the
day, and "this is when the Palestinian and Israeli stances, remarks
and actual readiness to honor the commitments will become clear,"
Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Since last Thursday, Ross has been shuttling between Arafat and
Netanyahu in a bid to win their acceptance of a U.S. plan calling
on Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank over 12
weeks, linked to Palestinian crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians and Israel are cool to the plan. Israel
has said the withdrawal scope is unacceptable and that it would
pull out from no more than 9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians insist that Israel carry out three significant
pullbacks by summer this year under U.S.-brokered agreements
signed last year between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
