<HEADLINE> Romanian Premier Resigns Under Coalition Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Romania's prime minister Victor
Ciorbea resigned Monday under increasing pressure from coalition
partners on charges of incompetence.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister had already announced his resignation to his
ministers, said private television ProTV broadcasting live from
the government's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea would announce his resignation in a television address
to the nation. President Emil Constantinescu was expected to
accept the resignation in a separate television appearance.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, whose critics have accused him of
incompetence and laxity, has been in trouble since not only his
coalition partners but a dissident group within his own dominating
Christian Democrats called for his departure.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea, close to President Constantinescu, has always insisted
he was ready to resign but that the political line of his own
Christian Democrats prevented him from doing so.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea was elected mayor of the capital, Bucharest, in 1996,
before taking over as premier in November of the same year.
