<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday sent a letter to Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos,
expressing the U.S. government's willingness to continue to help
Angola in its peace process until final peace materializes in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Clintons's special assistant, Joseph Wilson, who is
accompanying Clinton on his current six-nation Africa tour, said
after he passed Clinton's letter to Santos, that in the letter
Clinton mainly talked about the present situation of the peace
process and its impact on U.S.-Angola relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. government urged the Angolan government
and the former rebel National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) to continue their efforts for the final peace in
the country, and open wider prospect for U.S.-Angola relations.
</P>
<P>
Wilson said that the recent progress in Angola convince people
that the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol would be fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
On the new timetable for Angola's peace process, which sets
March 31 as the final day for the final peace, he reiterated that
the work left unfinished is very important for final peace, and
the U.S. wished both the government and UNITA to fulfil their
promises and finish all the work according to the new timetable.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's current visit, he said, is to introduce new U.S.
African policy and have a better understanding of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Wilson arrived in Luanda Monday to deliver Clinton's letter to
Santos. He is to join Clinton's delegation in Botswana later in
the day.  
