<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes U.N. Position on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government welcomed
the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's position that talks for a
peaceful settlement in Cyprus should be achieved within the
framework of bi-communal negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides told a news briefing
that a statement by Annan's spokesman Saturday contained many
positive points especially "the reaffirmation that the basis on
which bi-communal talks are conducted will not change."
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to Fred Eckhard's proclamation that "talks
between the two leaders are the only framework within which the
two communities in Cyprus are treated on the basis of full
equality."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Annan met with Turkish Cypriot leader
Raud Denktash in Geneva on Saturday. During the meeting Denktash
reportedly insisted that future talks for an overall settlement in
Cyprus should be conducted on state-to-state basis, not on
bicommunal basis, as has been the case for years.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said Annan voiced disappointment over the impasse in
solving the Cyprus problem and urged Denktash to resume talks with
President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of talks between the island's Greek and Turkish
communities were conducted under the auspices of Annan's peace
envoy, but were stalled last summer after the European Union was
prepared to start accession talks with the Cyprus government on
March 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Denktash upped his ante, refusing to resume peace talks unless
his Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus is internationally
recognized. The breakaway state is now recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides told reporters that the Cyprus government hoped the
international community, the European Union and the United States
will engage with more vigor, conviction and pressure to lead
things to an intercommunal dialog for a correct procedure for a
resolution of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over 37 percent of the island following a
short-lived pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
