<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Meet to Build Micro-Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Micro-finance leaders from
14 African countries started here Monday a three-day meeting on
building micro-finance networks in Africa.
</P>
<P>
This is the second micro-finance meeting with an aim to build
African regional and country-level micro-finance networks which
is jointly organized by Women's World Banking (WWB) and the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP). The first meeting was
held in July 1997 in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Bekele Wolde Abajifar, Executive
Assistant to the governor of the National Bank of Ethiopia said,
"the opportunities for the development of micro-financing
institutions in Africa can be conceived within the context of
improved political climate, the light that we have started to see
by way of efforts of states and citizens to promote peace and
democracy, and the efforts to development market economies."
</P>
<P>
Wolde Abajifar described the micro-financing as a new venture.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The fact that licro-financial institutions cater to
the needs of low income groups which constitute the vact majority
of the population in our sub-region, and also the fact that
nearly half of these are women who shoulder most of the burden in
maintaining family and society would mean that the efforts of
women's world banking is bound to succeed."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, UNDP representative to
Ethiopia Henrik Obesen stressed the importance to provide finance
services to the poor people in Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to Obesen, more than 50 percent of the African
population lives in poverty with no or very limited access to
basic social and economic services.
</P>
<P>
Millions of poor people in Africa are self-employed, engaged
in small trading or retailing activities or micro-enterprise in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, many famlies combine very small
micro-enterprise activity with farming and largely depend on it
for family income. The majority of these micro-entrepreneurs have
no access to formal financial services.
</P>
<P>
He said that providing financial services to the poor is
possible indeed with imagination and determinations even at a
very large scale. Women's world banking and UNDP are trying to
bring these successful experiences from all over the world to
African institutions through this initiative of regional
networking of practitioners to build african microfinance
institutions, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to an inventory carried out by women's world banking
and the UNDP in 17 African countries, nearly 80 percent of them
mobilize savings and provide micro-loans which is much higher
than among most Latin American or Asian micro-finance
institutions over 50 percent of the clients are women.
</P>
<P>
These institutions are reaching the rural and urban poor and
the average loan size is under 300 U.S. Dollars and more than 50
percent of these institutions have a repayment rate of 90 percent
or more.
</P>
<P>
Women's world banking was conceived during the first UN World
Conference on Women held in Mexico City in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Today, it is the only women-led global network that aims to
open the world's financial system to low income women. It has 43
affiliates in 35 countries in the world, including 12 African
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
