<HEADLINE> Drought in Guyana Draws International Response </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and
several countries have assisted Guyana in fighting drought.
</P>
<P>
U.N Development Program (UNDP) has allocated 65,000 U.S.
dollars for drought assessment and mitigation and fund-raising
efforts, UNDP said in a press release on Monday. The World Food
Program is mobilizing food aid for affected areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
Canada and Norway have pledged a total of 220,000 U.S.
dollars for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
About 15,000 indigenous people in Guyana are facing food and
water shortages and about 2,500 rice and sugar farmers are in need
of relief assistance because of a severe drought blamed on El
Nino. 
</P>
