<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Satisfied With Start of EU Accession Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has expressed
satisfaction with the start of the Cyprus-European Union (EU)
accession talks which was launched in Brussels, Belgium, Monday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the talks as "historic," Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said that he expects an unhindered accession course will
proceed and that any existing problems will be solved prior to
Cyprus' EU membership.
</P>
<P>
He said he regrets at the Turkish Cypriots' refusal to
participate in Cyprus' negotiating team. "Unfortunately, there has
been a negative stance by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash and
Ankara, both for their participation in EU accession talks and
the resumption of talks for a Cyprus solution," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He noted "we don't want them to feel there is hostility between
us, because the fact is that such a thing is non-existent."
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the Greek Cypriot side expects that a Cyprus
settlement will be reached that would allow cooperation of the two
communities for the island's entry into the EU.
</P>
<P>
The accession process for Cyprus and five other countries was
launched in Brussels in the presence of the foreign ministers of
the 15 EU member states and the 11 applicant countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU will hold on Tuesday inter-governmental conferences with
the favored six, namely, Cyprus, Poland, the Czech Republic,
Hungary, Slovenia and Estonia.
</P>
<P>
A proposal by Clerides for the participation of Turkish
Cypriots in Cyprus' negotiating team was turned down by Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has threatened not to attend future U.N.-led peace
talks on Cyprus and to integrate to Turkey his breakaway state in
northern Cyprus if the EU goes ahead with accession talks with
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek-Cypriots dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus in 1983, which was only recognized by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
