<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Two French rightwing regional
leaders who allied with the far-right National Front (FN)
continued to defy protests on Monday, ruling out any possibility
that they will resign from the presidency of regional councils won
with FN votes.
</P>
<P>
The regional president of the industrial base of Rhone-Alpes
Charles Millon, who was re-elected with 35 votes from the FN, said
that he is the executive of the region, no matter people like it
or not.
</P>
<P>
Millon, who is defense minister under the former conservative
government, has failed to select vice-presidents of the regional
council because of boycott by leftwing and other rightwing
deputies.
</P>
<P>
From 150,000 to 180,000 people demonstrated in a dozen major
cities in France to protest the alliance between the rightwing
politicians and FN.
</P>
<P>
The president of French Catalonia Jacques Blanc, who was also
elected with FN votes, Monday rejected the protests and said he
has begun working "in service of this region which I love."
</P>
<P>
"The republic, it is not in the streets or in great
declarations. It is the decision of the polling boxes," he said in
Montpellier, capital of French Catalonia, where 10,000 people
protested his alliance with FN on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The other three regional presidents elected with FN votes have
resigned. 
</P>
