<HEADLINE> Ranariddh's Return Is a Step Forward: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan hoped that the return to homeland of Cambodian Prince
Norodom Ranariddh will assist in the holding of free and fair
elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General welcomes the return of Prince Norodom
Ranariddh on March 30 after an absence of nearly nine months,"
Annan said in a statement issued here by his spokesman on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The event is a result of efforts led by the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and supported by the United
Nations to help Cambodia find a satisfactory solution to its
political crisis, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
While Ranariddh's return "is a significant step forward, much
work still remains to be done to ensure that the elections fully
do justice both to the terms of the Paris Agreement and to the
gains of Cambodia during UN Transitional Authority in Cambodia
(UNTAC) and since," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
UNTAC was formed in 1992 with a mandate to implement the Paris
Agreement signed on October 23, 1991, to end Cambodian conflicts
through a comprehensive political solution.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh won a 1993 election and agreed to a power-sharing
coalition with Second Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
The Prince was overthrown by Hun Sen last July when he
travelled abroad. He returned under a peace plan aimed at ensuring
that he take part in the elections due in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
