<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The German government Monday announced
that it planned to spend an extra 600 million marks (327 million U.S.
dollars) this year on job creation, easing the country's
record high unemployment since 1930s.
</P>
<P>
According to Norbert Bluem, Social Welfare and Employment Minister,
most of the new funding will be allocated to eastern Germany, where
the jobless rate tops 21 percent, compared with 10.4 percent in the
west.
</P>
<P>
At present, Germany's unemployed number 4.8 million.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment has emerged as one of the toughest issues facing
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's centre-right government. Kohl is seeking his
fifth four-year term after 16 years in office.
</P>
<P>
The German general election is scheduled to be held in September.
Opinion polls have shown stronger support for the main opposition
Social Democrats.  
