<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Investigate Rwanda Policy Under Mitterrand Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Faced with charges that it played a
negative role before and during the 1994 genocide in Rwanda,
France has decided to investigate its policy toward the African
state under former President Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
Following a much publicized visit by U.S. President Bill
Clinton to Rwanda on March 25, the role France once played in that
tiny central African state is being more and more debated by the
local media.
</P>
<P>
The local dailies of Le Monde and Le Figaro are publishing
investigative reports on the 1994 genocide, in which about one
million Tutsis were killed by Hutus.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government under Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
decided last week to cooperate with a parliament commission,
headed by Socialist deputy Paul Quiles, which is specialized in
investigating the policy of France toward Rwanda during the
Mitterrand era.
</P>
<P>
The commission, established after two French college scholars
accused the former government of supporting the Hutus, will have a
second hearing on Tuesday on the possible French implication in
the Hutu conspiracy in the killings.
</P>
<P>
But the French authorities are divided over how much power
should be given to the Quiles commission.
</P>
<P>
The Communist parliamentary group,supported by the Greens, has
proposed giving the commission some legal power, while the more
conservative parties prefer restricting the commission to "a
mission of information."
</P>
<P>
The revelations to come out could oblige some French officials
serving under the former government to testify at the
International Tribunal in Arusha, Tanzania, established by the
United Nations to punish those who committed the genocide.
</P>
<P>
The French National Assembly will vote soon on the Communist
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Four years after the genocide, some key questions about the
French role in Rwanda remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
Who shot down the French military helicopter which carried
Rwanda President Juvenal Habyarimana and Burundian President
Cyprien Ntaryamira on April 6, 1994, still remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
The death of President Habyarimana triggered the massacres in
Rwanda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
