<HEADLINE> Turkey Refutes Charges over Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel on Monday criticized international institutions for making
a fuss about his country's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a human rights conference here in which governors
and police chiefs participated, Demirel said that the state is
responsible for preventing human rights violations and the most
important measure for preventing these violations is "an open
regime" - a reference to the secular government.
</P>
<P>
He said "there are many good things happening in Turkey
concerning human rights, but several people and international
institutions always talk about the bad things in Turkey."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey's Interior Minister Murat Baseskioglu also
denied there exists a human rights problems in the country. "Other
countries claim that Turkey is faced with the problem of human
rights, this is not true," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism is also an international problem, which Turkey
faces. Turkey does not give any concessions from human rights
while struggling with terrorism," he added.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "there are several elements which threaten
our state and constitutional order, such as terrorism and
fundamentalism."
</P>
<P>
"The security forces also have to struggle with fundamentalism,
but we are well aware of the fact that we have to act within the
framework of the principles of a democratic society and a legal
state as they are foreseen in the Constitution," Baseskioglu added.
</P>
</TEXT>
