<HEADLINE> Schroeder Reelected as Lower Saxony State Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Schroeder, candidate of
Germany's main opposition Social Democrats (SPD) for chancellor in
the country's September general elections, was Monday formally
reelected for a third term as premier of Lower Saxony state.
</P>
<P>
"A fundamental improvement in our nation's prospects is only
possible through renewal. This change is necessary," he said in a
speech at the regional parliament in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
"I will fight so that this change comes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder won a landslide victory in the March 1 local
elections with 47.9 percent of the vote, compared with 35.9
percent for Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union
(CDU), and with 44.3 percent for him in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The victory enabled Schroeder to win over SPD chairman Oskar
Lafontaine in their contest for the SPD challenger of Kohl in the
general elections.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, 53, has been leading the 67-year-old Kohl in opinion
polls for months.
</P>
<P>
Kohl is seeking a fifth four-year term in the September
elections after 16 years in office. 
</P>
