<HEADLINE> Egypt, Syria, Saudi Arabia to Discuss Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia are
to hold a high-level meeting within a few hours in Saudi capital
Riyadh to examine the outcome of intensive efforts to restart the
stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt' Middle East News Agency Monday quoted informed sources
as saying that the gathering will focus on possible contacts and
proposals to help keep the momentum of American mediation in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and his Syrian counterpart
Farouq al-Sharaa reportedly have arrived in Riyadh Monday evening
for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since the
Israeli government began construction of a new Jewish settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem in March 1997. The two sides are also
wrangling over the scope and schedule of an overdue Israeli
pullback from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross is currently on a Middle East
mission in an attempt to dissuade the Palestinians and Israelis
from their bottom lines on the long-delayed West Bank redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Washington wants Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank in exchange for Palestinian security cooperation as part
of a package deal to end a year-long Mideast peace stalemate. But
Israel so far refused to accept the U.S. proposal. 
</P>
