<HEADLINE> Over 20 Palestinians Injured in Clashes in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Clashes erupted on Monday
between Palestinians and the Israeli troops in the West Bank and
over 20 palestinians were injured, according to the Jerusalem
Media and Communication Center (JMCC).
</P>
<P>
The clashes occurred while the Palestinians held demonstrations
and strikes in different cities and towns and villages in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip to mark the 22nd anniversary of the Land Day
to protest the land confiscation policy of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
In Bethlehem, a large number of Palestinians clashed with
Israeli troops near the Rachel's Tomb in the city and the Israeli
troops fired tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse the
protesters. During the clashes, 20 Palestinian students were hit
by rubber bullets, JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
Three Palestinian youths were reportedly injured by rubber
bullets fired by Israeli troops during clashes which erupted at
the Maloufuyeh check-point near Ramallah Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Six Israeli Arabs lost their lives on March 30, 1967, in
northern Galilee, in clashes with Israel soldiers over a land
dispute erupted following the confiscation by then Israeli
government of land owned by Arab villagers in Galilee. Both
Israeli Arabs and Palestinians mark the incident each year to
protest against the land policy of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Council has called on all
Palestinians, inside Palestine and elsewhere to mark the
anniversary on Monday with popular and mass demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police and defense forces are on high alert on Monday
on both sides of the 1967 ceasefire line, the Green Line, as
Israeli Arabs plan a series of strikes, marches and demonstrations
to mark the occasion.
</P>
<P>
In Israel, thousands of the Israeli Arabs held protest
marches and demonstrations in Galilee and Negeve areas. The
residents of unrecognized Arab villages, whose lands are
threatened with confiscation, also spent the day of planting
olive trees to mark the Land Day anniversary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
