<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Syrian, Saudi FMs to Parry Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Egypt
and Syria arrived in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, Monday on an
unannounced three-day visit to meet with their Saudi counterpart
on efforts to push ahead the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Amr Moussa and Syria's Farouq Al-Sharaa will hold talks
with Saudi Prince Saud Al-Faisal during their stay in Riyadh. The
talks are "part of a joint Arab drive to counter the anti-peace
policies" of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the Kuwait
News Agency (Kuna) said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli hardline policies on the peace process have sparked
wide-spread criticism from Arab countries and the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been deadlocked for a year
over Israel's construction of a Jewish neighborhood in Arab East
Jerusalem in March last year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia, the three heavy weights in the
Arab world, have urged the Israeli government to reverse its
current hardline policy and abide by the agreements it signed with
the Palestinians in order to rescue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in Riyadh was quoted by Kuna as saying that
the Egyptian capital Cairo would host a mini-Arab summit in May to
coordinate positions on the latest developments in peace-making.
</P>
<P>
But both Moussa and Al-Sharaa declined to speak to reporters
about their mission in Riyadh upon their arrival, Kuna said.
</P>
