<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Makes No Breakthrough in Advancing Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross made no breakthrough at his final meeting on Monday
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in advancing the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted a senior political source as saying that
after four rounds of talks with Netanyahu, Ross still does not
know the exact scope of the territory Israel is willing to hand
over to the Palestinians in its next troop pullback from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who just ended his
visit to the United States, also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
But Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon refused to meet Ross
in protest against the American peace initiative, which calls on
Israel to hand over 13.1 percent of the West Bank in the second
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, the leading hawk in Netanyahu's government, has
insisted that a redeployment of more than 9 percent will damage
the national security interest of Israel.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Uruguay's President Julio Maria on
Monday, Netanyahu denied that any agreement has been made between
Israel and the U.S. on the extent of next withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also reiterated that Israel should determine its
security needs by itself. But he indicated he did not want
confrontation with the U.S. administration, which he called as
Israel's "old friend."
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived in the region last Thursday in an attempt to
break the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, also
has held three meetings with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The peace envoy has said that he is going to report the
development to U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who will decide the next move to push forward
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
