<HEADLINE> Junic: There Can Be No Development Without Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- There could be no development
without economic reforms, Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Banko
Junic said in the northern Greek port city of Thessaloniki Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a business forum called "Greece and the Balkans: the
Emerging Market of Southeast Europe," Junic stressed that without
economic reforms, there could be no development, and without
development, the conditions for real democracy, freedom of
expression and all the other factors considered the primary
characteristics of contemporary democracies could not exist.
</P>
<P>
Without the cooperation of Yugoslavia, he added, cooperation in
the Balkans in any sector could not succeed.
</P>
<P>
Junic criticized the economic sanctions imposed by the
international community on Yugoslavia, saying that the sanctions
had cost the country's economy some 100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Direct economic damage from the embargo amounted to 6 billion
dollars over the past six years, he said, adding that the amount
will increase dramatically in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
He said that the sanctions also had repercussions upon the
sectors of education, health and social stability.
</P>
<P>
Attending the forum were government officials, entrepreneurs
and business representatives from the Balkan countries. 
</P>
