<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Financing for Schools in El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) announced here Monday the approval of 71 million U.S.
dollars in financing of the rehabilitation, reconstruction and
expansion of school infrastructure in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed to improve the physical learning
environment of 20 percent of the nations pupils. It is estimated
that some 250,000 children from predominantly poor families will
benefit from the program.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, 1,391 classrooms in 538 schools will
be constructed to replace temporary classrooms that are rented,
borrowed, or unsuitable for teaching, and also to keep up with the
current demand in all areas of the country, especially isolated
rural communities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 1,806 classrooms in 293 schools will be repaired
and rehabilitated, including schools in remote areas and the three
technical centers of San Miguel, Zacatecoluca and Santa Ana.
</P>
<P>
The IDB financing is made up of a 69.84 million dollar loan
from ordinary capital and a 1.1 million dollars loan in Salvadoran
currency.
</P>
<P>
Local counterpart funds a total of 7.9 million dollars for the
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
