<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Romania Sign Pact on Weapons of Mass Destruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States signed a
pact on Monday with Romania, agreeing to provide Romanian border
guards with equipment, training and other services to help
interdict any smuggling of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen and Romanian Defense Minister Constantin Ionescu at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the U.S. will provide Romania with items that
range from binoculars to equipment to detect potential transfers
of chemical, biological or even nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that the spread of deadly chemical and biological or
nuclear weapons pose a serious threat to the United States and to
all peace-loving countries.
</P>
<P>
"Romania and the United States realize that we have to do all
that we can to prevent terrorists or rogue nations from acquiring
and using such weapons, and this agreement is going to make us
partners in that campaign," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cohen thanked Romania for its support in the United Nations,
where Washington sought Iraqi compliance with U.N. inspection
requirements on weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
On Romania's potential membership of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), Cohen said the nation "remains a
strong candidate" if the country continues its reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed, "No one can predict at this point when
there will be a future decision made on future countries coming
in."
</P>
<P>
Ionescu said, "For Romania, the NATO membership is a strategic
goal, and we'll fight for membership. I believe that in the
moment there will be some decision to be made, we'll be invited to
join NATO."
</P>
<P>
The defense minister stressed that " the strategic partnership
with the United States, which is for Romania a very important
partnership."
</P>
<P>
Ionescu hailed the agreement as "a step forward" in bilateral
cooperation between his country and the United States.
</P>
<P>
When NATO leaders decided last July to accept new members,
France and Italy insisted Romania should also be accepted together
with Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic. But Washington
opposed it and Romania's bid failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
