<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missiles That Downed Rwandan President Come from France: Figaro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The two Soviet-made missiles which
shot down a French military helicopter carrying Rwandan President
Juvemnal Habyarimana and Burundian President Cyprien Ntayamira in
1994 were from France, said the influential French daily Le
Figalo.  .
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro made the revelation on Tuesday by quoting two French
officers who spoke on condition of anonymity, and a pamphlet
written by Filip Reyntjens, a professor of the University of
Antwerp in Belgium who is specialized in African affairs and the
Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
In his 1996 pamphlet, "Rwanda: Three Dates Which Rocked
History," published by L'Harmattan publishing house, Reyntjens
said that the two SAM 16 Gimlet missiles that shot down the Falcon
50 helicopter "could be part of the pack sold in 1988 to Iraq" by
the then Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
"In the wake of the Gulf War, these missiles could have been
seized by the French contingent in the multinational force and
brought to France," said Reyntjens.
</P>
<P>
But he said that he has "never been in a position to verify
these crucial reports."
</P>
<P>
However, the speculations by Reyntjens were half-confirmed by
two unidentified French officers interviewed by Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
"Within the framework of my duties in Rwanda, I can testify
that France actually retrieved these missiles during the conflict
with Iraq," said one of the officers, who did not say whether the
missiles were later used in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Another officer said he knew that "there was an order
formulated between November 1993 and February 1994 asking for the
provision of two ground-to-air missiles."
</P>
<P>
He said he learned about the order from a French businessman
who died in 1997, and that the order "seemed to come from someone
close with former Captain (Paul) Barril," a former security
officer of the Elysee Presidential Palace in the era of President
Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
Barril was in charge of an anti-terrorist cell group for the
presidential security. After his retirement, he runs a security
business.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French Defense Ministry has rejected a request
by Le Figaro to interview Commander de Saint-Quentin, a French
army officer who inspected the scene of the crash of Falcon 50 in
Rwanda the next day after it was shot down on April 6, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The death of President Habyarimana immediately triggered the
massacres in Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Nations Seeks for Humanitarian Aid to Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations launched an
appeal here on Tuesday for 79 million U.S. dollars to ensure the
continuation of urgently-needed humanitarian and rehabilitation
assistance for Somalia throughout 1998.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the appeal is a separate request for 15.3
million dollars to meet the most pressing needs through June,
1998, in the wake of the massive floods in the country, according
to the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nearly the entire Somali population lacks access to education
and basic health services, the UN office said. Repeated outbreaks
of cholera, malaria, and one of the world's highest incidences of
tuberculosis have drastically lowered life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
The short-term objectives outlined in the 1998 Consolidated
Inter-Agency Appeal are:
</P>
<P>
-- To prevent a recurrence of widespread humanitarian
emergencies, including through the development of effective
monitoring and response capacities for humanitarian emergencies,
</P>
<P>
-- To strengthen rehabilitation and governance efforts which
represent the most minimal and essential needs required for
Somalia to exit the current state of crisis,
</P>
<P>
-- And to create a socio-economic environment conducive to the
return of refugees and the internally displaced by working with
local communities and administrative structures.
</P>
<P>
Activities include ensuring the provision of essential health
services through the supply of drugs and pharmaceuticals, training
of health personnel, ensuring access to safe drinking water,
preventing communicable diseases, and rehabilitating schools.
</P>
<P>
The UN office requested the international community to respond
generously to both appeals, to relieve the protracted suffering of
the Somali people and to provide a basis for the longer-term
rehabilitation and reconstruction of the country.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, the United Nations agencies operating
in Somalia have developed a common assistance strategy in close
conjunction with non-governmental organizations and donor
governments.
</P>
<P>
This strategy is based on the principle of joint programing and
greater coordination of efforts, within the larger context, of
area-based planning and implementation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Strategic Road Project Takes Shape in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Highways
Department Tuesday awarded consultancy assignments to a company
for the investigation and preliminary design of a new road project
called Route 10.
</P>
<P>
The proposed 17.5 KM-long route will stretch from north Lantau
to Yuen Long in "New Territories."
</P>
<P>
Works on the route are scheduled to commence in 2002 and will
be completed in 2007. The estimated cost for the project is around
22 billion HK dollars (2.82 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Mott Connell Limited will be responsible for examining the
engineering and environmental feasibility of the route.
</P>
<P>
The consultancy, at a lump sum fee of 89 million HK dollars
(11.41 million U.S. dollars), will help determine a single route
alignment as well as the preferred structural forms together with
their preliminary designs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Tuesday, Director of
Highways Leung Kwok-sun said this section of Route 10, together
with Deep Bay Link, Route 10 - Hong Kong Lantau Link and Route 7
(Belcher Bay to Aberdeen), would form part of the strategic
Western Highway between Hong Kong and Shekou in Shenzhen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
