<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tian'anmen Rostrum Getting Better Maintenance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The rostrum at Beijing's
Tian'anmen Square, which has been the site of many momentous
events over the past half century, is going to be given better
maintenance as part of the preparations for the People's
Republic's 50th anniversary celebrations.
</P>
<P>
No major repairs are needed, since the ancient building is
still in good condition and there has been routine maintenance
about once a year on the old brick-wood structure, according to
Lin Bingkui, of the Beijing government's Tian'anmen Area
administrative board.
</P>
<P>
For many Chinese, the rostrum is more than just an old building
left over from the imperial age. It's the site where the late
Chairman Mao Zedong announced the birth of the People's Republic
on October 1, 1949, and a place where important leaders mingled
with the ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
It was made a cultural relic with state protection in 1961,
and, since 1988, when it was opened up to tourists for the first
time, more than 15 million people have visited it.
</P>
<P>
Recently, a group of cultural relics and building specialists
were invited to have a closer look at the building to prepare for
the coming anniversary. They came to the conclusion that the
rostrum had been well preserved, nevertheless that there were
certain problems. Moisture, the decay of some wooden structures,
the old wiring, and the age of the power equipment all meant that
maintenance needed some attention.
</P>
<P>
The 34.7 meter-tall rostrum was first built in 1417, or the
15th year under the rein of Emperor Yong Le during the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644), and bore the name Chengtianmen. It was
destroyed twice by fire, and the present building was built in
1651, at which time the name was changed, Lin said. It then became
a sacred place where emperors held ceremonial events for issuing
imperial edicts.
</P>
<P>
For the past several decades, there has been only one major
repair job, Lin recalled, and that was in 1970. During that
refurbishing, the pattern of tiles was changed, with dragons being
replaced by sunflowers, but the main structure of the building was
maintained and reinforced, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
