<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls For Cooperation on Cultural Heritage Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This proposal was presented Tuesday by Li Yuanchao, head of the
Chinese cultural delegation to the Intergovernmental Conference on
Cultural Policies for Development held here from Monday to
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), was aimed at
promoting cultural development in the world.
</P>
<P>
Li Yuanchao, a vice minister of culture, said at the conference
that cultural heritages and resources in the developing countries
are being threatened with damage and diminishment as a result of
unscrupulous plundering, robbing and buying at high prices by big
powers.
</P>
<P>
"We should strengthen our efforts to protect all the tangible
and intangible heritage," he told government representatives from
more than 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the developed countries should commit themselves
to assisting developing countries to promote their national
cultures for the realization of a harmonious cultural development
among regions.
</P>
<P>
Li also appealed for consultations and communications among
different cultures in order to apply the principles of cultural
diversity in a broader context.
</P>
<P>
In an action plan presented at the Conference on Monday, UNESCO
urged all nations to spend an equivalent of at least 0.5 percent
of their economic output on cultural development within the next
10 years.
</P>
<P>
Federico Mayor, Director General of the UN cultural agency,
urged that national spending on culture recommended by the
organization should be included in government budgets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
