<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some of China's Elderly Showing Preference for Old Folks' Homes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Xiuge, a 74-year-old
retired middle school teacher in Shenyang, capital of northeast
China's Liaoning Province, got a room in a local "Senior Citizens
Apartment" despite strong opposition from four sons and a daughter.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to live with my children and add to their
troubles," she said in explaining her actions, "I'm well looked
after by doctors and nurses here and always have the company by
other senior citizens."
</P>
<P>
Many of China's senior citizens, either in response or reaction
to social progress, have gradually abandoned the traditional
practice of spending the remaining years of their lives with their
children, and have opted for life in an old folks' home,
especially in the cities.
</P>
<P>
According to a Civil Affairs Ministry official, there are about
1,500 old folks' homes in China caring for nearly 100,000 senior
citizens, 30 percent of whom are paying for their stay. In some
developed coastal regions, all senior citizens living in old
folks' homes pay for their accommodations.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1980s, these kinds of homes in China were a sort of
government-funded welfare institution that was only open to the
helpless aged who either had no income or could not work and had
no children to rely on.
</P>
<P>
But now, with a growing demand from senior citizens with decent
incomes or financial support from their families, some old folks'
homes have become more market-oriented and are now running their
own business.
</P>
<P>
Wang Baolin, the head of the Shenyang Old Folks' Home, said
that his home has started running advertisements in the local
media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Announces Five-Year Land Disposal Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
announced Tuesday that it is able to provide a total of 650
hectares of land for housing in the five years from 1998 to 2003.
</P>
<P>
The 650-hectare land is estimated to produce 345,400 flat
units, said Bowen Leung, secretary for Planning, Environment and
Lands of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), when
announcing the government's Five-Year Land Disposal Program (LDP)
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Five-Year LDP covered two parts -- land
disposal in 1998/99 and 1999/2000 and the projected land supply
for the following three years between 2000/2001 and 2002/2003.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that a total of 286 hectares of land would be
disposed of in the first two years, which have the potential to
produce 158,900 units for housing.
</P>
<P>
As regards the second part of the LDP, he forecast that the
land supply for housing for the following three-year period will
be 364 hectares which are expected to produce 186,500 units.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that among the various needs of the community,
housing has been accorded the top priority on the SAR government's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
The government would make available sufficient land for
achieving the long-term housing target of producing not less than
85,000 flats a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The sufficient provision of land will help stabilize property
prices in Hong Kong, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
"The government is fully aware that stable property prices are
important to the economy of Hong Kong. We do not wish to see a
sharp price increase, nor a collapse in the property market," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
