<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some of China's Elderly Showing Preference for Old Folks' Homes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Other homes for the elderly, to increase competitiveness and
attract more paying customers, are making an effort to improve
their facilities and their services. One survey has shown that
most old folks' homes in major Chinese cities now function as
multi-purpose centers with everything from medical care and
rehabilitation to entertainment.
</P>
<P>
China now has 130 million people above the age of 60, and much
of the country has seen the dawn of the aging society. There is at
the same time a shortage of facilities to care for senior
citizens, and only an average of six beds for every 10,000 elderly
people, according to existing conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is welcoming investment in the area, and
is encouraging the existing homes to expand by taking in more
paying customers, says Zhang Zhong, a Civil Affairs Ministry
official.
</P>
<P>
Xia Chuanling, a research specialist on senior citizens,
attributes the sharp increase in the number of the people willing
to pay for urban old folks' homes to China's rapid economic growth
in the past two decades and the family planning policy, and says
that, "As time goes by, more and more Chinese families will face
the heavy burden of having to support several senior citizens at
the same time."
</P>
<P>
It is important that the government establish a social system
that can help deal with this burden, Xia said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's VAT Up One Percent From April 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The value-added tax will be raised
by one percentage point to 16 percent in Germany up from Wednesday
to help finance the country's expensive social welfare system.
</P>
<P>
The VAT increase was decided last December as a compromise
between the German government and the main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) to avoid raising pension contributions to a
record of 21 percent of wages from the current 20.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The compromise, however, has provoked sharp criticism from
German business leaders who say it would curb retail demand while
increasing inflation by about 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Challenging that view, the Berlin-based German economic
research institute DIW said on Tuesday that although the VAT
increase would somehow dampen the economic growth, an increase in
pension contributions could be even more harmful.
</P>
<P>
DIW also said it did not see any serious inflation danger
coming from the VAT increase because the inflation rate in Germany
is now at a record low of 1.1 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
