<HEADLINE> Minister: Malaysia No Base for Rebel Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia does not want to
become a base for any rebel groups from neighboring countries as
it wants to maintain good relations, Deputy Home Minister Tajol
Rosli Ghazali said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister made the remarks when asked to comment on
Monday's incident where 14 Indonesian illegal immigrants from
Acheh forced their way into the compound of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) office here to seek sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
The 14 Indonesians, who reportedly fled from the Lenggeng
immigration detention camp in the eastern state of Negeri Sembilan
last Thursday, claimed themselves as political refugees and
refused to be deported together with other illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia views those who entered the country illegally as
illegal immigrants, irrespective of whether they are Acehnese or
from other provinces in Indonesia, he said when met by reporters
at the lobby of the Parliament House here.
</P>
<P>
"We don't differentiate one group of Indonesian illegal
immigrants from another. They are all the same," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We also don't want Malaysia to become the base for rebel
groups from the Philippines, Thailand and Indonesia. We want to
maintain good relations with our neighbors," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tajol Rosli said Malaysia was still waiting for confirmation
from the UNHCR office as to whether the 14 Indonesians were
political refugees as claimed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama, Malaysia has agreed to a request from the UNHCR here for
time to determine if the 14 Indonesians still camping in the
compound of the UNHCR office here are legitimate asylum-seekers.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Deputy Inspector-General of Police
Norian Mai told reporters here Tuesday police would only act on
the 14 Indonesian illegal immigrants once they leave the UNHCR
compound.
</P>
<P>
The group faces action for not having valid travel documents
and for escaping from the Lenggeng detention camp, Norian said at
a news conference here, adding police were prepared to evict them
from the UNHCR premises upon request from the agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
