<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- In one of its most ambitious undertakings, the Japanese
Government plans this week to set in motion a far-reaching program
that it hopes will infuse the country's financial landscape with
the prowess of its manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
-- The American mediator for the Middle East, Dennis B. Ross,
concluded a four-day shuttle in the area apparently without
breaking the year-old deadlock in Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations. After Ross held a fourth and final meeting with
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, a senior Israeli official said
that the American proposal for a partial withdrawal from the West
Bank was flatly rejected.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- A team of scientists is zeroing in on a mysterious
AIDS-fighting substance distilled from a distinctly unlikely
source -- the urine of pregnant women. The existence of the
substance has been suspected for several years, but its precise
chemical identity has proved elusive.
</P>
<P>
-- The House on Monday night emphatically rejected the
Republican leadership's campaign finance bill as angry Democratic
and GOP critics decried the voting process as a "fraud" and "sham"
that barred consideration of their bipartisan plan to curb
fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- OPEC agreed to cut crude oil production by 1.25 million
barrels a day, after a meeting that yielded specific pledges about
how much each country will now produce. Still, the cuts, about 1.5
million including cuts by non-OPEC producers, fall short of
amounts promised March 22 and likely won't boost oil prices
immediately.
</P>
<P>
-- U.N. weapons inspectors have searched six of the eight Iraqi
presidential sites covered by the recent access agreement between
Baghdad and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan. The inspections
should be completed this week, a U.N. official said. 
</P>
