<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Kenya and
South Africa are resolved to work towards enhancement of
bilateral ties in the economic, scientific, technical and
cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here Tuesday, a joint communique
was issued at the end of a three-day official visit to Kenya by
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo who arrived here on
March 29.
</P>
<P>
Nzo and his Kenyan counterpart Bonaya Godana said in the
communique that cooperaion between the two countries would be
strengthened with the conclusion of the Trade Agreement under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers agreed that the Agreement on the Avoidance
of Double Taxation and Prevention of Evasion with Respect to
Taxes on Income and the Protocol on Protection of InvestmeNt
should be concluded as quick as possible.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the two ministers also discussed
the possibility of establishing a Joint Commission aiming at
enhancing mutual relations and the signing of a Memorandum of
Understanding on cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
After signing the communique, Nzo pointed out that all these
draft documents discussed during his visit would provide legal
basis for the promotion and consolidation of relations between
South Africa and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The South African minister described his visit to Kenya as "of
very great significance in consolidating relctionship between our
two countries."
</P>
<P>
He announced that one of the highlights in the two-day talks
with his counterpart Godana is to propose a date for a state
visit by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes well, the visIt is pos{ibly to take place
on August 13 this year, said Nzo, adding that Godana has accepted
his invitation to visit South Africa before August. 
