<HEADLINE> Russia, Namibia to Increase Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and his visiting Namibian counterpart Sam Nujoma Tuesday signed
a joint declaration on bilateral relations, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration, the two sides will develop
relations as friendly states and partners, guided by common ideals
of peace, respect for human rights, democracy, sovereign equality
and generally accepted international law.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also signed an agreement on the prevention
of dual taxation and income tax evasion and an accord on the
development of the diamond industry.
</P>
<P>
During their talks held in the Kremlin, the two leaders also
agreed to set up an inter-governmental commission for trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said that Russia's presence in Africa needs to increase,
according to Russian Presidential Spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky added that Yeltsin and Nujoma also agreed that
Russia would monitor Namibia's fish resources and expand fisheries
jointly with Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian president arrived in Moscow on Sunday on his first
official official visit to Russia since Namibia gained
independence from South Africa in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky added a Russian delegation would soon visit
Namibia to expand bilateral trade and economic ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
