<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Total Deposits Continue to Rise in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Total deposits in Hong Kong
recorded an increase of 1.4 percent in February this year based on
a modest growth of 0.2 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics published by the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority show that HK dollar deposits rose by 1.9 percent,
reversing a decline of 2.2 percent in January while foreign
currency deposits grew by 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the month, HK demand deposits rose by 3.8 percent while
savings deposits increased sharply by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rises reflected partly the return of "lai-see" cash to the
banking system in the form of demand and savings deposits after
the Lunar New Year, with cash held by the public declining by 13.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, time deposits dropped by 1.5 percent in February,
along with falling interest rates and reduced volatility in
regional financial market.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by currency, U.S. dollar deposits rose by a modest 0.1
percent, having increased strongly by 4.8 percent in January,
while non-U.S. dollar foreign currency deposits rose by 1.6
percent, following a growth of 1.8 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Figures also show that total loans and advances fell by 2.9
percent in February due to the slowdown in economic activities
across Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
