<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of China Providing On-Line Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign exchange bank,
the Bank of China (BOC), will gradually provide on-line electronic
banking services and is expected to have them for its branches in
major cities this year.
</P>
<P>
Li Yongjia, the deputy-general manager of BOC's information
technology office, told a press conference here today that it has
successfully completed a pilot operation in its Beijing, Shanghai,
Tianjin, Guangzhou, and Qingdao branches and this has laid a solid
foundation for electronic banking.
</P>
<P>
People in these cities can do business at any BOC branch bank
or in an ATM machine. Foreigners can also have access to
international networks.
</P>
<P>
The new electronic services come courtesy of Canada's SLM
Software Inc., which announced today that it will soon open a
Beijing office to provide full support for the system.
</P>
<P>
BOC is the 15th largest bank in the world. Two weeks ago,
China's first on-line transaction was done through the BOC
network.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
