<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi has accepted an invitation to visit South Africa later
this year, South African Foreign Affairs Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first official visit by Moi to South Africa,
South African Press Association quoted department spokesman Marco
Boni as saying.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was extended on behalf of President Nelson
Mandela by Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, who was in Kenya to
discuss bilateral issues with his counterpart Bonaya Godana.
</P>
<P>
Nzo, who ended his three-day visit to Nairobi Tuesday, had
successful talks with Moi on the "consolidation of the
relationship" between the two countries, Boni said.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued Tuesday said the two countries were
preparing a trade agreement aimed at boosting trade and
investment ties.
</P>
<P>
Kenya was South Africa's largest trading partner on the
continent outside of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC). Exports to Kenya in 1996 totaled 954 million Rand (190
million U.S. dollars) while imports from Kenya came to 123
million Rand (24.5 million dollars), according to Boni.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was the biggest direct foreign investor in Kenya
last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Official relations between the two countries were resumed in
1992 after a 29-year break.  
</P>
</TEXT>
