<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Exports Drop 17.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's export earnings
in February recorded 60 million US Dollars, down 17.4 percent
from January's figure, according to the Bank of Tanzania (BOT).
</P>
<P>
Earnings from both traditional and non-traditional exports
have declined, says a latest bank report reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report also notes that the trade deficit in February
reached 49.3 million US Dollars compared with a deficit of 25.7
million US Dollars recorded a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from traditional exports reached 35 million Dollars,
a decrease of 23.9 percent from January.
</P>
<P>
The decrease has been attributed to a decline in both volume
and prices of exported commodities.
</P>
<P>
All traditional exports recorded decreases in prices except
for cotton and tea whose unit prices increased by 13.0 percent
and 7.6 percent respectively, the BOT report said. As for export
volume, only coffee and tobacco recorded increases in February.
</P>
<P>
On non-traditional exports, the BOT report notes that earnings
from this sector decreased by 5.9 percent from 26.9 million
Dollars to 25.3 million Dollars during the period under review.
</P>
<P>
The decrease has been attributed to low earnings from cotton
yarn, manufactured coffee, fish and fish products.
</P>
<P>
On an annual basis, export earnings for the year ending
February 1998 decreased by 11.5 percent to 686.6 million Dollars
from 775.9 million Dollars recorded in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The report says that for the year ending February 1998
receipts from traditional exports decreased to 350 million
Dollars from 426.9 million Dollars recorded in the same period in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The yearly decline in export earnings is largely due to a
decrease in volumes of all traditional exports except for sisal
whose volume soared by 60.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
