<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Syrian FMs End Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Egypt
and Syria left Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, Tuesday after holding
intensive talks with their Saudi counterpart in a bid to revive
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa, who arrived in Riyadh Monday on an unannounced
visit, and Saudi Foreign Minister Saud Al-Faisal focused their
talks on the peace process in light of latest U.S. efforts to
revive the peace talks, according to Kuwait News Agency (KUNA)
reports from Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Israeli insistence on building a new Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem last year and its intransigency over Israeli
redeployment in the West Bank stalled the Middle East peace
process and so far international efforts in reviving the process
have failed to bring any positive results.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources were quoted by the KUNA as saying that the
three foreign ministers made a comprehensive review of the
current situation in the stalemated Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa presented full details of U.S. Middle East Peace
Coordinator Dennis Ross's talks Monday with Egyptian leaders over
the U.S. initiative to salvage the deadlocked peace process. Ross
Monday ended his shuttle diplomacy with Israeli and Palestinians
leaders, which failed to find any solution.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers stressed that the Middle East would never
enjoy ever-lasting peace and stability without a just,
comprehensive and balanced peace.
</P>
<P>
The ministers' talks are part of a joint Arab effort to counter
the intransigency policies of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, diplomatic sources in Riyadh said while speculating
that they might have agreed on holding a mini-Arab summit next
month that could also include the Palestinian National Authority,
Lebanon, Jordan and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia, the three heavy weights in the
Arab world, have frequently urged the Israeli government to
reverse its current anti-Arab policies and abide by the agreements
it signed with the Palestinians in order to rescue the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Egyptian capital of Cairo would play host
to a mini-Arab summit to coordinate positions on the latest
developments regarding the Middle East peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
