<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Promote Tourism by Staging World-class Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government said
Tuesday that it plans to promote the tourism industry by staging a
series of world-class events in the next five years with the
support of a 100-million HK dollar (12.82 million U.S. dollar)
International Events Fund (IEF).
</P>
<P>
Announcing details of the use of the fund, Amy Chan, executive
director of the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA), told a press
conference Tuesday afternoon that a steering committee will be set
up to oversee the fund.
</P>
<P>
The committee will include representatives from the Finance
Bureau, the Economic Services Bureau and the HKTA itself, as well
as professional experts from related fields, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA noted that the IEF, which was first announced by Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa in his policy address late last year and approved by the
Provisional Legislative Council on March 23 this year, will be
used solely to facilitate the staging of international,
world-class events in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The staging of world-class events in such fields as sports,
art, culture, entertainment, dining, and conventions and
exhibitions, as well as tourism-related activities, can help
create job opportunities and enhance the cultural and living
standards of local residents, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that this will help attract an additional
150,000 visitors to Hong Kong, thereby bringing in an extra one
billion HK dollars (128 million U.S. dollars) in tourism receipts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, extra consumption and commercial investment by
overseas organizations will also be induced through the staging of
events here.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that other social benefits brought by major events
include the enhancement of Hong Kong's international reputation,
the promotion of cultural exchanges and an increase in job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The SAR administration has taken concrete measures to help
underpin the efforts of Hong Kong's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the financial budget last month, Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang said that apart from providing funding for tourism
facilities and attractions, the government will make two tax
concessions on tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
The first is to reduce the rate of Hotel Accommodation Tax from
five percent to three percent and the second is to reduce Air
Passenger Department Tax from 100 HK dollars (12.82 U.S. dollars)
to 50 HK dollars (6.41 U.S. dollars) when the new airport at Chek
Lap Kok opens on July 6.
</P>
<P>
The administration also assigned 7.85 million HK dollars (one
million U.S. dollars) to the HKTA to develop a tourism data bank
to enable it to disseminate information to local and overseas
travel agencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
