<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Proposes to Fund Iraqi Oil Sector: Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed
Mehdi Saleh said on Tuesday that United Nations oil experts have
proposed that funds be allocated for Iraq to buy spare parts for
its oil sector, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Saleh, however, complained that the money suggested by the
experts, who visited Iraq a week ago, is less than what Iraq needs
to upgrade its capability to pump more oil, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say how much money the experts have suggested
and the amount Iraq needs for its oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is barred from exporting oil under U.N. sanctions imposed
in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. But an oil-for-food deal
between the two sides has granted it an exception to sell 2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six months to buy food and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved a resolution last month to
increase the amount of oil Iraq can sell to 5.2 billion dollars in
the third phase of the deal starting from December.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq has said it can pump no more than 4 billion dollars
worth of oil due to the shortage of spare parts and equipment in
the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iraqi minister said that a U.N. delegation will
arrive here soon to discuss with Iraqi officials the distribution
plan for the third phase of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, however, insists that the new plan be left to itself
rather than the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said that Iraq has given and will give priority to
friendly countries which have positive stance on lifting the
embargo when it seeks suppliers of humanitarian materials.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has minimized its imports from Australia in response to
its negative position in the recent U.S.-sparked crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Australian government will take
positive stance and pull back its troops from the Gulf region to
resume economic relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States threatened to take military actions last
month to force Iraqi compliance with the U.N. resolutions.
Australia sided with the U.S. and sent troops to the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Saleh accused the U.S. of continuing to block its companies
from carrying out contracts signed with Iraq for the second phase
of oil-for-food deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
