<HEADLINE> BMW: Rolls-Royce to Remain Independent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- German carmaker BMW, winner of the
bid for British luxury carmaker Rolls-Royce, said on Tuesday in
Munich that Rolls would remain independent after the takeover.
</P>
<P>
Rolls would continue to base in Crewe, Britain, and its
workforce would be left unchanged, Bernd Pischetsrieder, BMW
managing board chairman, said.
</P>
<P>
"BMW will continuously develop the range of Rolls-Royce and
Bentley models," he added.
</P>
<P>
BMW, which makes the V12 engine for Rolls-Royce, offered 340
million pounds (570 million U.S. dollars) last Wednesday in the
bidding for the luxury carmaker, beating Germany's largest
carmaker, Volkswagen, and a group of Rolls-Royce fans.
</P>
<P>
The deal is yet to be approved by a conference of shareholders
of Vickers engineering group, the parent company of Rolls.
</P>
<P>
Rolls-Royce was put up for sale by Vickers earlier this
year. The deal with BMW will let Britain's last carmaker be taken
over by foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Rover is now owned by BMW, and Jaguar and Aston-Martin were
acquired by Ford Motor Company in the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
