<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Failure of Ross's Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAALE ADUMIM (West Bank), March 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday denied that the United State
Middle East Peace Envoy Dennis Ross failed in his mission to break
the deadlock in Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
During his tour in a Jewish settlement in Maale Adumim of the
West Bank, Netanyahu told reporters it was not true that Ross
returned to Washington "empty-handed" as local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu noted that Ross presented to him "very good" ideas
over the peace process during their four rounds of talks in
Jerusalem. He said that they discussed these ideas and will
continue the talks in the near future.
</P>
<P>
During his visit from Thursday till Monday, Ross reportedly has
present to Israeli and Palestinian leaders an American peace plan,
which calls on Israel to withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the West
Bank in the second redeployment, linked to the fulfillment of the
Palestinian commitment to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Early reports said that Ross did not succeed in reaching an
agreement with Israel on the scope of the next pullback, and also
failed in getting the Palestinians to make a detailed plan on
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
According to a consensus passed by Israeli Cabinet, any
redeployment of more than 9 percent will damage the national
interests of Israel.
</P>
<P>
And the right-wingers in the ruling Likud coalition have
declared that they will topple Netanyahu's government if the
prime minister carries out the redeployment without the
Palestinian guarantee to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu also denied that there are "problems" in his
coalition government, noting that he also doesn't think that the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has made efforts to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who wrapped up his four-day visit in the region Monday
night, is going to report the development to the U.S. president
Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who will
decide the next move to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli-Lebanese peace talks, Netanyahu said he believes
that the Lebanese Army has the ability to maintain the
security in south Lebanon. He stressed that Israel is willing
to withdraw from Lebanon if the Lebanese government renews its
authority in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
