<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Investment Decreases Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in Indonesia
is expected to reach only 20 billion U.S. dollars this year, a
sharp drop from the previous years' annual average investment of
32 billion dollars, a senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government decided to offer more incentives to
investors to curb the decline of the foreign investment, State
Minister for Investment Sanyoto Sastrowardojo said after meeting
with President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the foreign investment in the first quarter
of 1998 reached 5.1 billion U.S. dollars spread in 307 project
proposals.
</P>
<P>
In the same period in 1997, the foreign investment reached 6.5
billion dollars but the number of projects was only 221.
</P>
<P>
Most foreigners invested in gas and electricity, housing and
industrial estates, agriculture, chemical and metal industries,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
On domestic investments, Sanyoto said that in the first quarter
of this year, some 17.8 trillion rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals
8,500 rupiah at present) have been invested in 94 projects, a
sharp fall compared to the same period last year when the figure
reached 36.9 trillion rupiah in 165 projects.
</P>
<P>
Sanyoto said President Soeharto instructed him to consult other
ministers before announcing the government's plan to give
additional incentives to new investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
