<HEADLINE> Tourism Zone Featuring Buddhist Culture to Open in Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A tourist attraction featuring the
Buddhist culture is scheduled to open April 12 in beach-side
Sanya, a city on Hainan Island.
</P>
<P>
The new scenic spot is the first phase of the gigantic Nanshan
(southern hill) Culture Tourism Zone designed to cover 35 square
kilometers of land and dozens of square kilometers of sea area.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 kilometers to the west of Sanya the attraction, which
is expected to cost 6 billion yuan (722.89 million U.S. dollars)
to build, will become the largest Buddhist shrine in south China.
</P>
<P>
The projects that have already been completed include the
rebuilding of Nanshan Temple; a Buddhist square featuring Tang
Dynasty (681-907) arch; a Guanyin Bodhisattva (the goddess of
mercy) pavilion; and a flower garden.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of construction includes a floating statue of
Guanyin more than 100 meters high; imitation Buddhist buildings
modeled after India and Nepal, an elderly people's garden and a
happiness square.  
</P>
</TEXT>
