<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Declares Suspension of Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Tuesday declared a unilateral suspension of offensive military
operations against the New People's Army (NPA) rebels starting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of operations will last for 91 days or up to the
midnight of June 30, the day President Ramos steps down when his
six-year single term ends.
</P>
<P>
In his recommendation to Ramos, Defense Secretary Fortunato
Abat said the plan is aimed at encouraging maximum participation
of the citizenry, including insurgents, in promoting "a free and
peaceful atmosphere" in the coming May elections.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, it hopes to further strengthen the gains
that the peace negotiations with the NPA has achieved so far," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that his order will not cover normal law enforcement
functions and actions to be taken to protect the people, the
communities and government troops.
</P>
<P>
The order will have the effect of a presidential issuance of a
safe-conduct pass to all members of the NPA during the period
covered "provided that no firearms, explosives and other deadly
weapons are carried by them," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the order shall be respected by elements of the
Armed Forces and the Philippine National Police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
