<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What Supports The Stronger Baht? (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 by Xu Haijing
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Like a thunderstorm, the Thai
baht devalued sharply overnight after it was set floating on July
2, 1997, hitting the record low of 57 baht against the greenback
on January 12 this year.
</P>
<P>
Again like a tropic thunderstorm, the currency quickly enjoyed
a clearing sky after that and has been stabilized at about 38
against the U.S. dollar in the recent two weeks.
</P>
<P>
What can be the explanation of the myth of the baht
thunderstorms, it is wondered.
</P>
<P>
A review at the activities at the political stage may provide
some of the answers.
</P>
<P>
First, the Thai House of Representatives vetoed the
no-confidence motion submitted by the opposition parties against
the government on March 21.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the government, headed by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai,
was provided with a stable political environment for its efforts
to bring the economy back onto the right track.
</P>
<P>
Second, the highly-evaluated visit to the United States by
Prime Minister Chuan was also seen as a big push for the baht to
go up.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan's U.S. trip between March 11 to 17 was
hailed both domestically and internationally as a move which
successfully improved Thailand's image and boosted confidence
among foreign investors in the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
Western countries, including the United States, and
international organizations such as the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank, gave thumb-up to the Thai
government's work since it took office last November.
</P>
<P>
The Chuan government has followed the IMF prescription of
financial reform by closing 56 of the 58 suspended financial
institutions. It also kept a high interest rate in a bid to
stabilize the currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
