<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Telecommunications Industry Enters New Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The telecommunications industry
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) entered a new
era on Tuesday morning, after the Hongkong Telecom International
Limited surrendered its exclusive external licence to the SAR
government.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony following the formal surrender of the
exclusive licence, Secretary for Economic Services of the SAR
government Stephen Ip said the early termination of the
exclusivity in external telecommunications was of great
significance for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Not only will Hong Kong consumers gain direct benefits
amounting to 17 billion HK dollars (2.18 billion U.S. dollars),
the liberalization of the international telecommunications market
will bring in a large amount of investment, stimulate the economy
and create employment opportunities -- not just in
telecommunications but in the service industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "it will eliminate the hindrance caused by
the exclusivity in the introduction of new technology and will
help maintain Hong Kong's position as the pre-eminent
telecommunications hub in the region."
</P>
<P>
The SAR government proposes to issue licenses for competitive
external telecommunications services which will take effect from
January 1, 1999 and for facilities-based competition in the
provision of external services from January 1, 2000. With this
schedule, Hong Kong is expected to become one of the most
liberalized telecommunications markets soon within the World Trade
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
