<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks May Resume Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The peace talks in Burundi
may soon resume following the release of two former leaders of
the central African nation, a Tanzanian newspaper report said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The international mediator in the Burundi political conflict,
Tanzania's former president Julius Nyerere, has sent his envoy
Judge Mark Bomani to Burundi for discussions with warring parties
before the resumption of peace talks, the Guardian paper here
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Secretary General of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim has arrived in Dar es Salaam for
the talks with Nyerere and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa on
the Burundi issue.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere insisted that one of the conditions to resume Burundi
peace talks is the release of former Burundi presidents,
Jean-Baptiste Bagaza and Sylvestre Ntibantunganya, and also
Speaker of the Burundi National Assembly Leonce Ngendakumana.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere said that the conditions, set during the last Great
Lakes summit in Kampala last year, should be respected first.
</P>
<P>
"We will act only when the conditions are met," he told the
Independent Television (ITV) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Bagaza and Ngendakumana were freed from house arrest recently,
paving the way for the Resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The move shows that "there are signs that could make the talks
resume soon," a government official was quoted by the Guardian as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks were stalled last year after the
Burundi military junta led by Pierre Buyoya said it had no faith
in Nyerere, who is an advocate of imposing economic sanctions on
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by OAU, have imposed
economic sanctions on Burundi since August of 1996 after Major
Buyoya toppled a civilian government of President Ntibantunganya
in July, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
