<HEADLINE> Junta Members on Trial in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The trial of former Koroma junta
members charged with treason started Monday in Freetown, media
reports from Sierra Leone said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports available here, some 21 former
ministers and top officials of the ousted military junta of
Sierra Leone were arraigned before the Freetown Magistrate Court
No. 1, all charged with treason.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, they would face death penalty or long terms of
imprisonment, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Those appeared before the court Monday include five civilians
who acted as ministers and deputy ministers under the Koroma
junta, which was overthrown in mid-February by the West Africa
peace-keeping force, ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Others are former head of state Sankow Philip George, popular
broadcaster Dennis First, former spokesman of the junta Jibrin
Massaquoi and arms dealer Steve Bio.
</P>
<P>
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's former secretary, Bakut Bayo,
was also brought before the court.
</P>
<P>
Bayo worked briefly with the junta and later fled to Ghana. He
returned to Freetown after President Kabbah was reinstated on
March 10, nine months after he was toppled by Koroma's military
coup last May.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG declared a fortnight ago that about 1,400 persons loyal
to the Koroma junta were being held as Prisoners of War in
Freetown.
The hearing of Monday's trial was adjourned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporeans Asked to Use Water Wisely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Singaporeans have been asked by
the authorities to use water wisely as Singapore's water stock has
gone down within the last month from 85 to 73 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Public Utilities Board (PUB) said on Tuesday that the
country's water levels are expected to drop further in the dry
months ahead.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that in March, the average daily demand for water
was 1.3 million cubic meters, which is 3.2 percent higher than the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The PUB therefore has appealed to the public to use water
wisely to help conserve the country's water stock.
</P>
<P>
It suggested avoiding the use of drinking water to water lawns,
wash cars and fill swimming pools, for example.
</P>
<P>
The PUB also said that it is monitoring the water situation and
will implement more conservation measures if the dry weather
persists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
