<HEADLINE> 18 drown in Uganda waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 31 (Xinhu`) -- Eighteen people, including four
health workers, drowned in recent days in Uganda, ''The New
Vision'' reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Three doctors and a nurse of Mulago hospital, the most famous
one in the country, Drowned Sunday when their mini-bus plunged
into river Mayanja at Wamika, some 56 kilometers northwest of
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
In another accident, 12 fishermen drowned when a canoe
capsized in lake Kyoga, northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
There are still another two feared dead in another accident in
Mayanja river, police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said the tragedy in Wamika was caused by
collapse of two bridges in the river due to floods.@The rescue
operation is still on. Four persons involved into the accident
have already been rescued, but another two medical workers of
Mulago hospital are missing by Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The remains of the four victims were not retrieved by Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Laurence Kaggwa, the Director of Mulago Hospital, said the
accident was a ''disaster that has robbed us of talented
medics.''
</P>
<P>
One of the victims, Dr. Francis Mubiru, was an influential
medic and has wide reputation in local population for his show in
a local radio every Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The driver of the mini-bus ignored the remarks by local police
and local residents to stop the mini-bus, said John Kashaka,
Mubende district police commander.
</P>
<P>
The mini\bus was on its road back to Kampala from a wedding
ceremony when it plunged into the water, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The accident which claimed the lives of 12 fishermen was
caused by a storm. The canoe is on its way from Lira to
Nakasongola through the lake of Kiyoga. 
</P>
