<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Up in Directionless Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed only
marginally higher Tuesday with focus amid directionless trade on
the close out of the March share price index contract.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 3.2 points higher at 2744.2
points, around the mid-point of the day's trading range.
</P>
<P>
"There was a lack of overseas leads," a Shaw Stockbroking
broker said, "Most of the overseas markets were all down
(overnight) and I didn't think we were going to rocket away
today."
</P>
<P>
The slower start on the Nikkei this morning took any potential
spike out of the market, the broker said.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Industrial Average index dropped 13.96 points
overnight and Australian investors will be watching Wall Street
Tuesday night for leads and any announcements from the scheduled
Federal Reserve Monetary Policy meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the physical market, the all industrials index added 6.2
points to 4702.0 points while the all resources index was 0.7
points higher at 1182.9 points.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks recovered part of Monday's drop with the sector
index climbing 17.9 points to 5626.3 points.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank eased seven cents, the Commonwealth
added 3.4 cents and ANZ slipped five cents, while Westpac rose 18
cents.
</P>
<P>
Global media giant News Corp lost four cents to 9.97 Australian
dollars while its preferred shares were six cents cheaper.
</P>
<P>
In other industrial stocks, paper and packaging concern Amcor
eased five cents after it named Russell Jones as the new managing
director.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment shares remained steady on 3.89 Australian
dollars on turnover of 15.4 million shares, the top traded stock
of the day.
</P>
<P>
In the gold sector, the index dipped 5.2 points to 1195.9
points with the gold bullion price slipping 2 U.S. dollars per
ounce to 300.40 from the Sydney close Monday of 302.40.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 286.15 million shares worth 890.55
million Australian dollars (587.75 million U.S. dollars) with
falls outnumbering rises 582 to 502. 
</P>
</TEXT>
