<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, IMF Reach Agreement on Monetary Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) and the Indonesian government have reached an agreement on
Monetary policies, IMF Director for Asia-Pacific Operations,
Hubert Neiss said here Tuesday without giving details.
</P>
<P>
"We have discussed monetary policies and have reached a
reasonable conclusion," Neiss said following a meeting with
central bank, Bank Indonesia Governor Syahril Sabirin.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Neiss, who has been leading the IMF team
here since March 18, said the IMF and Indonesia will soon end
nearly two weeks of talks on Indonesia's monetary and economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
"There are still points to be discussed ... corporate debt,
that is still an issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, Indonesia's foreign debt totaled 137.4
billion U.S. dollars, 73.9 billion dollars of which were incurred
by the private sector. The huge private sector debt has been
blamed as one of the causes of the economic crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah has lost more than 70 percent of its
value against the U.S. dollar since July last year. As a result of
the monetary crisis, the country has been facing with spiraling
inflation, growing unemployment and other serious economic and
social problems.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia signed an agreement with the IMF at the end of
October last year in exchange for a bailout package of more than
40 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Indonesia promised to conduct wide ranging
economic, financial and trade reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
IMF gave its first 3 billion U.S. dollars tranche to Indonesia
in December last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the Fund withheld the second tranche worth 3 billion
dollars earlier this month because of the so-called lack of
reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the past 13 days, both sides discussed monetary policies,
banking sector, state budget, structural reform and external
corporate debt.
</P>
<P>
Neiss refused to specify the outcome of his meeting with the
central bank governor, saying the two sides wanted to have good
discussions, with no single point to be left undiscussed.
</P>
<P>
"We want all issues to be discussed fully and completely. Only
after this could we say that the discussions have been completed,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PR. Narvekar, IMF senior adviser to Indonesia, said
there will still be another round of talks between Indonesia and
the IMF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) closed lower Tuesday in the absence
of interest as the market awaited for the announcement of merger
plans by finance companies.
</P>
<P>
As for mergers, Arab-Malaysian Finance and Affin Finance were
the latest to announce their merger plans while news about other
mergers were made known after the close of the stock trading.
</P>
<P>
State Bank released a statement later in the day saying that
all finance companies have responded to the merger call.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index, moving in
a very tight range, fell 3.44 points to 719.52, the all-share Emas
Index erased 0.26 of a point to 182.09, the Industrial Index was
1.49 points lower at 1,296.63 and the Second Board Index shed 0.04
of a point to 179.81.
</P>
<P>
Losers edged gainers by 301 to 299 while 174 counters were
unchanged and 143 untraded.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover was 140.633 million shares worth 379.304
million ringgit (about 103.919 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The main board volume dropped to 123.267 million shares valued
at 332.888 million ringgit (about 91.202 million U.S. dollars)
from Monday's 133.749 million shares worth 309.893 million ringgit
(about 84.902 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover was 17.366 million shares valued at
46.415 million ringgit (about 12.716 million U.S. dollars) against
17.444 million shares worth 40.062 million ringgit (about 10.975
million U.S. dollars) Monday.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals fell to 10.489 million shares valued at 18.792
million ringgit (about 5.148 million U.S. dollars) from Monday's
27.852 million shares worth 84.205 million ringgit (about 23.069
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 6.943
million shares traded, industrial products 9.874 million shares,
construction 14.390 million shares, trading/service 30.811
million shares, Infrastructure 903,000 shares, finance 20.829
million shares, hotels 1.056 million shares, properties 12.418
million shares, plantation 4.839 million shares, mining 908,000
shares, trusts 21,000 shares, closed/fund 62,000 shares and loans
20.211 million shares. 
</P>
