<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
decline on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) lost another 19.38 points to close at
1629.18 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices weakened after a thin session
amid slight profit-taking in the absence of leads to spur the
market. They noted that the STII posted gains early in the day,
but a lack of follow-through by investors reversed the market's
direction.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that as the reporting season had come to
an end, therefore, little news was expected in the short-term to
move the market.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank further to 206.68 million units,
valued at 304.4 million Singapore dollars (about 189.07 million
U.S. dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 242 to 91, while
253 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Ber Group was the most actively traded counter as it registered
a turnover of 11.34 million units. It was followed by Renong which
had 11.23 million shares traded. Easyknit was next with 10.93
million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Jurong Shipyard led the gainers of the day as it rose by 25
cents to finish at 8.4 Singapore dollars. ASEAN increased by 20
cents to end at nine U.S. dollars. WTK was up by 15 cents to close
at 2.58 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 70 cents to end at 35.6 Singapore dollars. Bukit
Sembawang fell by 60 cents to close at 12.6 Singapore dollars.
City Developments Warrant98 and UOB (United Overseas Bank) Foreign
lost 50 cents each to finish at 5.3 and 8.95 Singapore dollars
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
