<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Slumps on Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The falling Japanese yen
overshadowed Australia's trade figures and pushed the Australian
dollar lower Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar has largely been a puppet of yen trading
in recent days, as the time draws near for the end of Japanese
financial year, and speculation grows as to the year-end
valuations of the Nikkei (share market index) and yen," said
Citibank chief economist Stephen Koukoulas.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 66.34 U.S. cents, from 66.68 U.S.
cents Monday.
</P>
<P>
The yen again took center stage Tuesday, despite market
sentiment that the release of February's balance of goods and
services data may swing the focus back to the domestic front, said
SBC Warburg Australia Foreign Exchange Director John Radinoff.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said the balance on goods
and services was an adjusted deficit of 321 million Australian
dollars (211.85 million U.S. dollars) in February, a narrowing
from a 556 million Australian dollars (367 million U.S. dollars)
deficit in January.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose two percent, adjusted, during the month while
imports remained virtually steady.
</P>
<P>
Radinoff said the Australian dollar pushed up to its highs for
the day after the data release.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar closed the local
session at 87.03 from 87.65 against Japanese yen and at 1.2294
from 1.2104 against Deutsch marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
