<HEADLINE> S. Korea Expects ASEM to Help Overcome Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 31 (Xinhua) -- South Korea is betting on the
Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) to help bring the country out from its
financial crisis starting late last year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs and Trade Minister Park Chung-soo also voiced
Tuesday his hope that the meeting, the second of the kind, could
help South Korea take another leap in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, of 10 Asian countries and their 15 European Union
counterparts, is scheduled to open Wednesday in London to further
their course launched in 1996 for an Asia-Europe partnership.
</P>
<P>
President Kim's trip to London bears economic importance, in
addition to political and diplomatic significance, said Kim
Taedong, senior secretary of economic affairs for the president.
</P>
<P>
For South Korea, now amid the financial crisis caused by
corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions,
the three-day event is a chance to mobilize support and help.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Dae-jung will meet, in the first overseas trip
since he was sworn in as the head of state last month, with heads
of government from Britain, China and Japan, Park said.
</P>
<P>
He will meet Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji for a bilateral fishery
agreement and on China's constructive role in the ongoing
four-nation meeting over a permanent peace in the Korean
peninsula, said Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
