<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound in Tokyo on Public Funds Injection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rallied in Tokyo with
the key Nikkei index ending just above the 16,500 line Tuesday,
the last day of fiscal 1997, after the apparent injection of
public funds into the market.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 264.13 points or 1.62 percent
from Monday's close to 16,527.17.
</P>
<P>
But the benchmark index fell far short of the 18,003.40 mark
hit at the end of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all First Section
issues, added 10.43 points or 0.34 percent to 1,251.70.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section increased to an estimated 650
million shares from Monday's 360 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Tuesday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Brisk buying of Nikkei index futures in the last 30 minutes of
trading triggered arbitrage-buying in the cash market, helping the
key index rebound to some extent, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index, however, failed to recover all of Monday's
476.22 point plunge to 16,263.04.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outnumbered gainers 678 to 477, with 103 remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
