<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Dissolves Information Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has officially dissolved
the Information Ministry in a bid to promote press freedom, the
Qatari News Agency (QNA) reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move came in a decree issued by Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad
Bin Khalifa al-Thani on Monday, the QNA said.
</P>
<P>
The decree ordered to transfer the department of foreign
publicity and publication and the government-owned QNA under the
Information Ministry to the Foreign Ministry, according to the QNA.
</P>
<P>
A new body will be set up to take over the department of
culture, art and heritages of the outgoing ministry.
</P>
<P>
Qatar began considering the dissolution of the Information
Ministry in 1996 when the ruler of the Gulf island country had the
idea to free the media of government curbs.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari emir has introduced a number of liberal policies,
including lifting press censorship and allowing newspapers to
criticize cabinet ministers and government policies, since he took
power from his father in a bloodless coup in June 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
