<HEADLINE> Iraqi Minister Concludes Visits to Oman, UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Justice Minister Shabid
al-Maliki left here Tuesday, wrapping up week-long visits to Oman
and the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the UAE's official Wam news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During the visits, Shabid met with Oman's Sultan Qaboos Bin
Said and UAE's President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan and
briefed them the latest developments in Iraq, in particular the
implementation of a deal between Baghdad and the United Nations
(U.N.) on arms inspections, Wam said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement signed late February provided Baghdad must
unconditionally allow U.N. arms inspectors access to all sites
suspected of containing weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Omani and UAE leaders told Shabid during his visits that
Baghdad should continue complete cooperation with the U.N. to
avert a possible use of force by the United States and Britain,
who keep strong military presence in the region to monitor a test
of the implementation of the U.N.-Iraq deal.
</P>
<P>
The two Gulf countries also pointed out that Baghdad's full
compliance with the U.N. resolutions related on dismantling of
weapons of mass destruction could help step up international
efforts to put an end on the Iraqi people's misery caused by the
U.N. trade sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Iraqi children and women have died
of shortage of food and medicine caused by the trade sanctions
imposed by the U.N. since the 1991 Gulf war against Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
