<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Israel's Intransigency Leads to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Indicating the depth of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace deadlock, United States peace envoy
Dennis Ross returned home empty-handed Tuesday without
compromising Israel's intransigency on its redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day shuttle mission between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), Ross held four meetings
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and three meetings
with PNA President Yasser Arafat in a bid to find a solution.
</P>
<P>
He also traveled to Egypt to hold talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak to seek his support in breaking the
one-year deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks due to
Israeli construction of Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Top on Ross' agenda was to persuade both sides to accept a
new U.S. proposal on Israel's second troop redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Washington was proposing a 13.1 percent Israeli pullout as a
compromise idea to patch up the sharp difference between the
Israeli and PNA's own plans. Israel is willing to hand over no
more than 10 percent of the West Bank in the second pullout, but
the PNA is demanding for at least 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Ross failed to lay even the groundwork for presenting
the U.S. plan following a series of intensive talks. The
reason: Israel's opposition to any plan calling for more than 10
percent pullout and its stalling over the obscure conception of
"reciprocity."
</P>
<P>
In fact, in his first two meetings with Netanyahu, Ross even
could not discuss the U.S. proposal because the Israeli leader
was only willing to talk about the so-called principle of
"reciprocity." Namely, Israel was demanding the PNA confiscate
illegal weapons, extradite murder suspects and revise the
Palestinian Covenant that calls for extermination of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Many people argue that Israel's demands for security have no
justification for further delaying the second redeployment which
was expected to have been completed last September. Indeed,
observers noted that the security demands have been used
repeatedly by the hardline Israeli government as a ploy to
placate its disgruntled rightwing members.
</P>
<P>
Undoubtedly, Israel's intransigency is largely due to the
inner pressure exerted by the powerful right-wingers within the
Netanyahu-led government. Netanyahu is well aware that he would
be ousted if he dares to alienate any ruling partner because his
government has only one-seat slim majority in the Knesset
(Parliament).
</P>
<P>
And it is obvious that the rightwingers will not hesitate to
rebel against Netanyahu if he succumbs to the U.S. pressure by
accepting the 13.1 percent pullout. The right-wingers have made it
clear that they would accomondate only a 9 percent pullout at the
most.
</P>
<P>
This was demonstrated in the boycott by the influential
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon of the last
Netanyahu-Ross meeting on Monday following reports that Netanyahu
was considering to accept a 11 percent pullout. Sharon warned at
the Sunday Cabinet meeting that a redeployment of more than 9
percent would endanger Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rightist camp also warned Netanyahu against
making any compromise on the redeployment issue.
</P>
<P>
Leading rightist coalition party, the National Religious Party,
formulated Sunday a list of demands for the Netanyahu-Ross
meeting, saying it would topple the government if Netanyahu
accepts the U.S. plan. The Land of Israel Front formed by 10
rightist lawmakers also threatened to topple Netanyahu if he
makes any compromise.
</P>
<P>
Israel's intransigency aside, the U.S. reluctance to exert
more pressure on Israel was another main reason for the failure
of Ross' mission.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials noted that Ross was making refinements to
the U.S. proposal to accommodate Israeli demands, even though the
proposal had already taken into account Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
In the coming days, Ross is to report to U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on his shuttle
diplomacy with the Palestinian and Israeli leaders before the
White House decides on the next move.
</P>
<P>
Albright has sent out clear warnings that Washington is losing
patience and the situation could fastly deteriorate unless the
concerned parties take hard decisions to move forward. But only
warning is not enough, and no immediate breakthrough is expected
as long as Washington still refuses to exert more pressure on
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
