<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Endorses New 3-year Deregulation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese cabinet Tuesday
approved a three-year deregulation plan to revive the country's
ailing economy, specifically 15 industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The plan, as described by officials, calls for liberalizing the
airline industry, the retailing of electric power, and allowing
foreign firms to enter Japan's digital broadcasting industry.
</P>
<P>
The plan will be effective from fiscal 1998 starting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes the new plan, along with the 16 trillion
yen (about 123.1 billion U.S. dollars) worth of economy-spurring
measures unveiled by the ruling Liberal Democratic Party last
week, will help the ailing economy recover, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the government will remove a rule restricting
the number of airlines operating on a single route. The
supply-demand balance of each route will not be taken into account
any more, allowing new carriers freely compete with their rivals.
</P>
<P>
The government will also end the monopoly on retail of electric
power by allowing companies which hold power generation facilities
to freely sell electric power.
</P>
<P>
As for broadcasting, the government will consider easing
regulations in fiscal 1998 to give foreign companies chances to
provide digital broadcasting services in the Japanese market using
their own communications satellites.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the plan, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told a
government meeting "We need to proceed with the deregulation in
order to comply with the people's demands, even though we know the
process may be painful for the time being." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
