<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires in Indonesia's East Kalimantan Cause 353 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The losses of the
three-month-long fires in Indonesia's East Kalimantan province
have reached about 3 trillion rupiah (353 million U.S. dollars), a
local government official said.
</P>
<P>
Fires continued to raze forests in the province and envelop
large parts of Kutai National Park and Great Soeharto Hill Forest
Park on Monday, reports reaching here Tuesday quoted a Kutai
regency official Soebianto as saying.
</P>
<P>
Soebianto said the fires, which started in January this year,
had already burned at least 131,000 hectares of East Kalimantan
forests.
</P>
<P>
He said the fires during the first three months of 1998 had
caused as much material damage as the total losses from sporadic
forest fires in the province over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
If the value of the wood was calculated with the exchange rate
of 10,000 rupiah to the U.S. dollar, total losses of the
three-month-long fires stood at 10 trillion rupiah (more than one
billion U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
The forest fires, he added, have not only affected East
Kalimantan but also neighboring Central Kalimantan, which has been
blanketed in haze from East Kalimantan for the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The haze has affected air transportation to and from Tjilik
Riwut airport, in Palangka Raya, Central Kalimantan, while
motorcyclists have already complained about eye irritations and
headaches.
</P>
<P>
Last year, at least 300,000 hectares of forests was ravaged by
fires in Sumatra and Kalimantan islands in Indonesia. In East
Kalimantan province fires destroyed 37,092 hectares of forest.
</P>
<P>
The disaster sent smog all over Southeast Asia, inflicting more
than 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in smog damage to Indonesia,
Malaysia and Singapore, 90 percent of which was attributed to
short-term health costs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
