<HEADLINE> Teachers Trained to Prevent Violence in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has started training its
teachers to prevent domestic violence, ''The New Vision'' paper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an inauguration ceremony of a week-long workshop
for the teachers-trainees at Kibuli police university in Kampala
Monday, police spokesman Bob Ngobi said the teachers are trained
to teac their students self-protection.
</P>
<P>
The training will be conducted by the police family protection
unit which deals with child abuse, rape, defilement and domestic
violenceon.
</P>
<P>
Rape and defilement are on the rise, said Stephen Onyu, the
senior assistant commissioner of police in charge of
administration.
</P>
<P>
The victims of domestic violence did not exclude women, but
include children, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
