<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Ranks Second in Per Capita Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The island province of Hainan has
utilized 7.4 billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment since
becoming a province in April of 1988.
</P>
<P>
This ranks the province second in the country in per capita
overseas investment after Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The province, which is also the country's largest
special economic zone, has also established 8,134 overseas-funded
enterprises during the last 10 years. Investors are from more than
20 countries and regions including the United States, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
As the investment structure has been constantly rationalized,
tropical high-efficient farming and energy development have become
new focuses for overseas investment. In 1997, 68 percent of the
overseas investment went to the agricultural sector, while the
proportion in real estate development declined.
</P>
<P>
In earlier years, overseas investment mainly was concentrated
in the cities of Haikou and Sanya, but now investors have been
active in 19 cities and counties.
</P>
<P>
And many leading multinational corporations have explored
business opportunities in Hainan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
