<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Financial Watchdog to Start Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 31 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Financial Supervisory
Commission, a watchdog of overseeing management of financial
institutions and directing reforms of conglomerates will go into
operation from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The commission composed of three bureaux and five task forces,
has been authorized to approve, supervise, restrict and review the
country's financial institutions except the three state-run banks
-- Export-Import Bank, Korea Development Bank and Industrial Bank.
</P>
<P>
The commission, which consists of officials and experts from
Finance and Economy Ministry, Bank of Korea, Deposit Insurance
Corp., will also serve as top financial policy-maker of the
economic crisis-engulfed country and will reform its financial
structure.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the International Monetary Fund
last December for a bailout loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, South
Korea has to restructure its economy and open its markets this
year.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected this week to order the top 30
family-owned conglomerates to reduce their debt ratio to 200
percent by the end of this year from current 400 percent.
</P>
<P>
The top 30 conglomerates are blamed for devouring bank loans
and shirking responsibility for producing the ongoing financial
crisis with their high debts build-up and over-expansion.
</P>
<P>
The loans extended by banks to the conglomerates in 1997
accounted for 25.1 percent of the entire credit of 442.59 billion
won (some 5.5 billion U.S. dollars), a surge of 43 percent over
previous year's 77.81 won. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
