<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Three major Lebanese companies will launch 350
million U.S. dollars worth of Global Depositary Receipts this year
to increase capital and expand business, the Lebanese Daily Star
newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three companies are Banque Liban-Francais and Byblos, both
among the country's 10 leading banks, and Solidere, a property
company leading a multi-billion-dollar drive to rebuild the
war-ravaged Beirut.
</P>
<P>
According to 1997 statistics, Lebanon's public and private
sectors have issued 2.7 billion dollars worth of Global Depositary
Receipts and other financial bonds.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The prices of imported drugs in Israel will drop
by about 25 percent in April after the Health Ministry approved a
new regulation.
</P>
<P>
Imported medication makes up about 40-50 percent of Israel's
drug market.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate reached 8.2 percent in
January, 0.1 percentage point up from that in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, industrial production remained flat in January
following monthly decrease of 1-3 percent from August-December
1997.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The net profit of the Bank Hapoalim, Israel's
largest bank, jumped about 21 percent in 1997 to 1.05 billion
shekels (about 294.94 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
This is the largest profit ever posted by an Israeli bank. In
1996, the bank's net profit was 868 million shekels (243.82
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An Indian industrialist delegation arrived in
Israel on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will meet with Israeli officials for the
technological incubator program in the Industry and Trade Ministry
and members of Israel Export Institute.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait Aircraft Corporation will receive one of
the two Boeing 777 planes on Tuesday under a deal signed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The second plane will be delivered in May.
</P>
<P>
The deal was supported by a 282-million-dollar loan accord
signed on Sunday by the Kuwaiti national carrier and a Gulf Arab
consortium led by the National Bank of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
