<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fires Expected to Worsen in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Forest fires in some western and
southern provinces in the Philippines are expected to worsen as
southwest monsoon winds intensify, the Philippine News Agency
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters and forest rangers are placed on red alert as
forest fires continue to threaten the remaining forests in five
provinces of northern Luzon and have started to encroach into the
fringes of timberlands of Palawan, the country's last ecological
frontier, and the famous Mt. Apo, the home to the endangered
Philippine eagle.
</P>
<P>
Rosalio Goze, director for operations of the Department of
Environment and Natural Resources, has ordered all fire fighters
to intensify their fire fighting programs, especially in the
drought-stricken areas which are highly vulnerable to forest
fires.
</P>
<P>
The limited number of forest firefighters and the increased
incidence of rest fires due to negligence and bad practices have
posed a serious problem to the government, Goze said.
</P>
<P>
Goze said the cultural practices among indigenous peoples of
using fire as a farm tool has not been fully regulated, thus
increasing the incidence of wild fire occurrences, especially
during a drought episode.
</P>
<P>
A total of 60 forest fires, excluding the wild fire still
raging in the province of Palawan, have already hit the country
since January this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Palawan fire which started last week has so far burned some
2,000 hectares of grasslands contrary to the earlier reports of
burned 15,000 hectares of timberland, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Urban Families See Decline in Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China's urbanites have to face a
tougher budget for family finance. Thirty-nine percent of Chinese
families in urban areas experienced a decrease in income last
year, according to the latest data from the State Statistical
Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The proportion of families in which incomes dropped in 1997 is
3 percent higher than the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report indicated that the proportion of victims of the
income slump is bigger in low-income groups rather than in
high-income ones. Among the low-income families, which account
for one-fifth of those covered by the bureau's random survey, 60
percent reported an income decline last year. This ratio is 6.3
percent higher than the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
However, only 20 percent of the high-income families, who
account for 20 percent of those covered by the survey, reported an
income decrease. This ratio is 3.8 percent less than the 1996
figure.
</P>
<P>
The incomes of urban families started a small-margin increase
since the beginning of this year. The SSB statistics show that
per capita income reached 777.8 yuan (93.71 U.S. dollars) in
families of 35 major Chinese cities in February, representing a
year-on-year increase of 1.2 percent in real terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
