<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elections Defer Formal Talks Between Manila, Muslim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA March 31 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming May 11 local and
national election will delay the start of the formal talks between
the Philippine government and rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF).
</P>
<P>
This was the statement made by Catholic Priest Eliseo Mercado,
chairman of the Quick Response Team, a peace body created by the
government and the MILF negotiators to oversee low-level conflicts
between their parties while peace process is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
Speaking over a local radio station Tuesday, Mercado disclosed
some members of the government negotiating panel are busy in their
political campaign and "that's why they could no longer perform
their task."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports cited that President Fidel Ramos urged the
government and MILF panel to come up with a final peace accord
before the end of his term on June 30.
</P>
<P>
But Mercado described the president's wish as "unrealistic"
citing time constraint.
</P>
<P>
However, Mercado, who is also majority floor leader of Southern
Philippines Council for Peace and Development, hailed the
president's vision on eliminating "disunity" among Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, MILF Vice Chairman for Political Affairs
Ghadzali Jaafar, shared the same opinion as that of Mercado.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said in the first place, they already anticipated the
deferment of the peace process due to the forthcoming political
exercise.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the MILF could still afford to wait for
the resumption of talks "as peace agreement cannot be done
overnight."
</P>
<P>
The MILF, the biggest Muslim rebel group in the country, has
been engaging in low-level peace talks with the government since
January 1997, but the two sides have not yet reached an agreement
on the start of the formal peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
