<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Vegetation to Attract Migrant Birds Away from New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese flight safety experts
and ecologists can heave a sigh of relief as a vegetation program
at an islet adjacent to the Pudong International Airport in
Shanghai is near completion.
</P>
<P>
Eleven kilometers east of the airport that is under
construction, Jiuduansha island is now covered by reeds and grass
planted since last year with a view to attracting migrant birds to
stop for a rest. These birds' usual stop is what is now the
international airport.
</P>
<P>
To avoid possible aircraft accidents caused by birds colliding
with flying planes after the new airport is operational at the end
of next year, experts are trying many ways to make migrant birds
change their flight paths as well as places of rest.
</P>
<P>
Workers have eliminated everything that could possibly become
food for birds in and around the airport while driving birds to
the nearby Jiuduansha islet.
</P>
<P>
In addition to planting reeds and grass, workers are also
enlarging the silt coverage on the island which is located at the
mouth of the Yangtze, China's longest river.
</P>
<P>
Each year, large flocks of birds from Australia fly over Pudong
in the western part of Shanghai on their way to and from their
breeding places in Japan, the Korean Peninsula and Siberia. Bird
watchers have found more than 150 kinds of birds among thousands
of taking a break at Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Experts are confident that by the end of next year, Jiuduansha
Island will become an ideal resting place for the migrant
birds. 
</P>
