<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Thai Officials Cooperate in Solving Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 U.S. and Thai Auto
Industry Officials Met here Tuesday to find ways of easing
Bangkok's transport problems and planning a future strategy.
</P>
<P>
The conference came after academic findings indicated that
Thailand could boost its slumping economy by easing the traffic
chaos.
</P>
<P>
The officials would work together with technical and industry
policy experts to hammer out recommendations for the Thai
government on how to develop its auto and transport policies.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference will deal with four major policy
areas, including transport infrastructure, fuels and energy,
vehicle emission and air quality, national automotive strategies
and policies.
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor Company Vice-President John Mctague said it was
important to find out practical solutions to traffic congestion
and the management of energy resources -- issues which are common
stumbling blocks in expanding markets.
</P>
<P>
Ford and another U.S. auto giant, General Motors, are the two
main sponsors of the conference organized by the U.S.-based
Society of Automotive Engineers Incorporation and its Thai
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Mctague said in a statement that U.S. studies had showed that
traffic congestion -- a feature of sprawling Bangkok -- has a
negative effect on the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand could increase its gross domestic product output by
as much as 30 percent by eliminating gridlock," he quoted a study
from Massachusetts Institute of Technology as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both Ford and General motors have production plants in
Thailand. Ford plans to begin producing a new compact pickup truck
in May, while GM is launching a passenger car.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Baker, GM vice-president for global research and
development, said the conference would help the Thai government
develop strategy and policy guidelines for planning and
implementation of a more efficient transport system to take the
country into the 21rst century.
</P>
<P>
Thailand became a Southeast Asian hub for auto manufacturers
during the booming 1980s, but the economic slump which began to
hit the country last year has left thousands unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Decreased consumer spending power at home and shrinking export
markets have hit the industry hard with most producers slashing
production and almost abandoning the local market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
