<HEADLINE> Minesweeping Operation on Sino-Vietnam Border Goes Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese troops in the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region have cleared mines from three million
square meters of land in an operation that began Nov. 28 along the
Sino-Vietnamese border.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Daxiong, deputy commander of the Guangxi Military Area
Command, said the minesweeping operation, the second since the
early 1990s when China and Vietnam restored relations, has removed
or exploded 21,260 mines of more than 20 types in four months.
</P>
<P>
The official said the first-phase work includes the clearing of
44 mine zones on nearly 7.78 million square meters of ground by
this May.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 engineers are engaged in the minesweeping
operation.
</P>
<P>
The second minesweeping operation is expected to clear 120
zones on nearly 20 million square meters of ground within three
years.
</P>
<P>
China's minesweeping operation has helped open 25 border trade
areas and mine ports of entry for trade between the two
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
