<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tian'anmen Rostrum to Be Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Concerned departments in Beijing
have started preparations for repairing the 300-year-old
Tian'anmen Rostrum and plan to complete the project before the
50th anniversary of the founding of new China on Oct. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Overall examination and evaluation of the Tian'anmen Rostrum
and nearby buildings are going on smoothly, according to today's
Beijing Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
Tian'anmen (the gate of heavenly peace) was first built in 1417
during the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) and was originally named
Chengtianmen. It was destroyed twice by fire and was rebuilt in
1651 during the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) and renamed Tian'anmen.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of the new China in 1949, Tian'anmen became
its symbol. The State Council made Tian'anmen a site under state
special protection in 1961. In 1988, the rostrum of Tian'anmen
opened to visitors.
</P>
<P>
The special structure of ancient Chinese buildings, mostly
built of brick and wood, has made the repair of Tian'anmen a
long-term task.
</P>
<P>
Examinations have disclosed that some of the wooden pillars
split open because of the arid climate and some were rotten, in
addition to water seepage at the roots of some golden pillars.
</P>
<P>
Experts also pointed out that electric equipment used there is
also out-of-date and needs to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Youth Daily reported that there were 17 registered
repairs of the Tian'anmen Rostrum between 1971 and 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
