<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Reins on Subterranean Water Tapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shangdong and
Jiangsu provinces have begun efforts to prohibit the overuse of
subterranean water when groundwater abuse is prevalent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Today's Guangming Daily quoted statistics from the Ministry of
Water Resources showing that China has used more than 90 billion
cubic meters of subterranean water, while the total resources are
290 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Groundwater extraction provides 17 percent of the country's
total water supply, with 12.66 million hectares of farmland and 35
percent of industrial and urban water supplies dependent on
subterranean sources.
</P>
<P>
The most serious problem is in the dry northern parts of the
country, where 17 provinces and autonomous regions use 88 percent
of the groundwater extraction. In this area, half of the water
supply for industrial production comes from subterranean sources.
</P>
<P>
Random overtapping has caused drastic drops in groundwater
levels and funnel-like zones, resulting in abandoned motor-pumped
wells, salt seawater penetration, land desertification, and
surface sinking.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in the coastal areas of Liaoning, Hebei and
Shangdong provinces indicate that an area of 1,433 square
kilometers has been affected by saltwater intrusion, which has
made more than 200 million cubic meters of local groundwater
resources useless, and made it difficult for more than a million
people and 400,000 head of livestock to find drinking water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0220 </DOCNO>
