<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Export Earnings Fall in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh earned 326.60 million
U.S. dollars from export in February this year, a decrease of
about 20 percent from 408.68 million dollars in January, press
reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure, however, demonstrates a rise of 17.5 percent over
export earnings in February last year, the reports said, quoting
the latest statistics from the Export Promotion Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The country's export earnings during the first eight months of
the current fiscal year (July 1997-June 1998) were recorded at
3.33 billion dollars, slightly short of the targeted 3.34 billion
dollars. Bangladesh has set its export target for the current
fiscal year at 5.02 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said the devaluation of currencies in some
Southeast and East Asian countries, which export similar items as
Bangladesh does, may be partly responsible for the fall in
Bangladesh' export in February.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU), the largest importer of Bangladesh
products, has relocated its import sources from Bangladesh to some
East European countries, such as Romania and Poland. This has
affected the nation's export, they said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the effect of EU's ban for half a year on
Bangladeshi frozen food, which ended earlier this year, would
linger for some time, according to the analysts. The country's
export earnings from frozen food fell to about 8 million dollars
in February as against the average monthly earnings of some 27
million dollars before the ban was imposed in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
