<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Approves New National Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's cabinet endorsed a new national land plan Tuesday
aimed at easing the concentration of population and industries in
Tokyo and Osaka, Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The government will start formulating guidelines to promote
strategies under the "grand national design for the 21st century
plan," which will be launched this year with completion dates for
its various phases ranging from 2010 to 2015, the Japanese news
agency quoted government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plan, the fifth of its kind, proposes establishing multiple
axes of development in four regions -- "northeast," "the Sea of
Japan coast," "the Pacific coast" and "western Japan" -- in a bid
to diffuse the country's population and industries now lining a
narrow corridor running from Tokyo to Osaka.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the creation of a "regional cooperation axis"
system, under which several municipal governments would share
administrative functions beyond their present jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
The plan includes six projects to build highways and bridges
over bays and straits across the country, while calling for
studies on the technology development and cost-efficiency aspects
of the projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Chinese Premier's Visit to Strengthen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain is hoping to establish a
basis for its relationship with China next century during the
forthcoming visit by China's new Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
British Minister of State of Foreign Affairs Derek Fatchett
told Xinhua that his government was looking forward to Zhu's
official visit from Tuesday to Thursday, his first trip abroad as
premier.
</P>
<P>
The visit by the new Chinese premier, who was appointed earlier
this month, has aroused great interest in various circles in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said that the visit "is bound to further promote our
relations".
</P>
<P>
John Beyer, director of the China-Britain Trade Group, said
Zhu's visit was of "great importance."
</P>
<P>
"He (Zhu) enjoys a high reputation of handling economic problems
with his abilities of clarity and decisiveness among British
economic circles. His visit will undoubtedly further develop the
relations between our two countries, so as to strengthen our
people's confidence in doing business in China," said Beyer.
</P>
<P>
Experts on Sino-British relations have expressed the belief
that Zhu's visit will play an important role in establishing and
developing Sino-British relations into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
According to Fatchett, relations between the two countries have
been going smoothly since China resumed the exercising of
sovereignty over Hong Kong last July.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair has repeatedly expressed the
hope that Hong Kong should become a "bridge" between Britain and
China after its handover.
</P>
<P>
Margaret Becket, chairman of the Board of Trade, said during
her visit to China last January that "the British government very
much hopes to create a new kind of relationship with China".
</P>
<P>
In its bid to cement relations with China, the British
government has been taking a series of positive measures,
including repudiating its support for the human rights motion
against China at the United Nations' annual human rights
conference in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
London has also increased visits to China by its high-ranking
officials and put special emphasis on economic and trade
cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook visited China in January while
Prime Minister Blair and Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott are
scheduled to do so later this year.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in bilateral relations has lead to an
inevitable impact on their cooperation in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between our two countries on global affairs
such as the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and environmental
protection has reached a new level. Being permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council, Britain and China should strengthen their
cooperation, so as to play an even more important role in the U.N.,"
Fatchett said at a recent seminar.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of Sino-British political relations has
provided favorable conditions for developing economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade volume reached 5.8 billion U.S. dollars in
1997. Britain is now the largest investor in China among the
European Union countries. It has set up more than 1,800 joint
ventures in China with a total value of 12 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Those who have visited China were all deeply impressed with
its economic dynamics and the ambition shown by its government and
people," Becket told British businessmen at a gathering after her
visit to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
