<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Leaves For Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji left
here today on an official visit to Britain from March 31 to April
2 at the invitation of British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
The premier is also scheduled to attend the second Asia-Europe
Meeting (AEM), which will be held from April 3 to 4 in London, and
take part in the first China-EU Summit during his stay in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Then, Zhu will pay an official visit to France from April 5 to
7 at the invitation of French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Zhu's entourage includes his wife Lao An, Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan and Minister Shi Guangsheng of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Among those seeing the premier off at the Great Hall of the
People were Chinese vice-premiers Li Lanqing, Qian Qichen, Wu
Bangguo and Wen Jiabao, vice-chairperson Peng Peiyun of the
Chinese National People's Congress Standing Committee, and
State-Councillor and Secretary-General of the State Council Wang
Zhongyu.
</P>
<P>
Local observers point out that China-EU relations have made
noteworthy progress in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, the EU proposed holding the first
China-EU Summit during the Second AEM and called for establishing
a regular meeting system thereafter.
</P>
<P>
The February EU Foreign Ministers Meeting ended with a decision
that the presidency and member countries would refrain from
tabling or cosponsoring a draft resolution against China in the
next session of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The latest development centered on the EU's March 25 adoption
of a new policy document entitled "Build a Comprehensive
Partnership with China".
</P>
<P>
The EU's wise decisions concerning China have been welcomed and
greatly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu's current European trip is expected to add impetus
to a long-term, stable and mutually beneficial Sino-European
relationship well into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
