<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes Republicans on Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
criticized Republican leaders in the House of Representatives
Monday for setting up a system viewed as guaranteeing the defeat
of campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement from Africa, where Clinton is on a tour,
he rejected the only reform alternative allowed by House
Republican leaders and said the Republican leaders appeared
"determined to thwart serious reform."
</P>
<P>
Clinton reiterated his support for a bipartisan bill proposed
by Representative Christopher Shays, a Republican, and
Representative Martin Meehan, a Democrat, the provisions of which
include banning unlimited and unregulated contributions to
political parties known as "soft money."
</P>
<P>
Despite a majority of House members supporting the bill, House
Republican opponents succeeded in crafting rules for floor action
that would sharply limit debate and require a two-thirds vote for
passage.
</P>
<P>
The House Republican leaders then put forward alternatives with
provisions that include limiting political activity by labor
unions and taking steps to crack down on the participation in
elections by non-citizens.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called such provisions "harshly partisan and plainly
unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Clinton described the Shays-Meehan bill as "the best chance in
years to reduce the role of special interests, give voters a
louder voice and treat fairly incumbents and challengers of both
parties."
</P>
<P>
The president said, "this measure has the support of a majority
of the Senate, and I believe that if it were allowed to come for a
vote, it would have the support of a majority of the House as
well." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
