<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Credit Scheme For Small, Medium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
launched a new credit scheme for small and medium enterprises
(SMEs), according to an official news release Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Development Bank, with assistance from the Asian
Development Bank, will invest 3,410 million Rupees (55.9 million
U.S. dollars) in the project.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank will provide credit guarantees worth 2,360
million Rupees (38.69 million dollars) to the participating credit
institutions as additional collateral for loans granted.
</P>
<P>
The release said the objective of the Central Bank's credit
guarantee scheme is to help small scale entrepreneurs, including
self-employed persons who could not raise loans from the banking
sector because of their inability to offer additional collateral
to support their loan applications other than project assets.
</P>
<P>
About 4,000 SMEs in Sri Lanka are expected to benefit from the
scheme.
</P>
<P>
Seven commercial banks, three regional banks and three
development banks in the country are participating in the project.
The loans, which are long term loans, are repayable within two to
ten years with a grace period from three months to two years
depending on the purpose of the loan, the release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
