<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Police Gets Tough on Drunk Driving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Thai police vowed to take tough
action against drunk driving, particularly during the Songkran
Festival on April 13-15, the Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Motorists found to have more than 50 milligrams of alcohol per
liter of blood would be punished, the police said.
</P>
<P>
That means two cans or small bottles of beer, or two glasses of
wine could lead a driver to jail.
</P>
<P>
Checkpoints would be set up on all main highways for random
tests using breathalysers, a senior police officer said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Land Transport Department's 1994 regulation against
drunk driving, which had been ignored until recently, offenders
are liable to a fine of 2,000-10,000 baht (52-263 U.S. dollars)
and/or a jail term of not more than three months.
</P>
<P>
The senior police officer said that from October 15 last year,
when the police started to enforce the law strictly, until
February this year, legal action had been taken against 128 drunk
drivers in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Without serious action, the country's losses due to road
accidents, most of which are caused by high alcohol consumption,
could reach 300 billion baht (7.9 billion dollars) per year
compared to the current estimate of 106 billion baht (2.8 billion
dollars) annually, the Public Health Ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
