<HEADLINE> Romanian President Accepts Premier Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu accepted Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea's
resignation Monday, but asked him to stay in office until the
nomination of his replacement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Ciorbea yielded to pressure and announced
his resignation in an televised address to the nation.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea has been under constant pressure to resign from most
parties within the ruling coalition, with many accusing him of
incompetence and laxity in carrying out promised economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government was plunged into crisis earlier this
year in a clash between the two major parties in the governing
coalition, the Democratic Party and Ciorbea's National Peasant
Party.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party withdrew from the coalition in January and
asked Ciorbea and his government to step down by the end of March,
but the National Peasant Party refused.
</P>
<P>
The crisis dragged on for months, causing havoc to the
country's political life, economy and social order and triggering
disturbances in various areas.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea's popularity as prime minister of the country has
dropped sharply in the face of growing calls from both within and
outside the parliament to quit office.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea was elected mayor of the capital, Bucharest, in 1996,
before taking over as premier in November of the same year.
</P>
</TEXT>
