<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ups and Downs of China's "King of Roasted Seeds" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Nian Guangjiu, in his 60s, has
never been as busy as he is now. Since the second half of last
year, he and his assistants have shuttled between China's large-
and medium-size cities to sell his "Shazi" (idiot) brand roasted
seeds.
</P>
<P>
In less than six months he has set up 96 shops across
China. Nian has become China's "king of roasted seeds" again.
</P>
<P>
"It's the prime time for private business," said Nian. "I have
to catch my last opportunity."
</P>
<P>
Nian was called "Shazi" (idiot) for his simple, honest face. A
recent documentary by Zhejiang TV Station cited his ups and downs
as an unique barometer of China's private economy.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s Nian, then a common street peddler with fine
seed-roasting skill, set up a firm to challenge the state
roasted-seed producers.
</P>
<P>
Soon, Nian's "Shazi" brand took over a big share of the market
because of the delicious taste and low price. Nian became one of
the first millionaires in China. Wuhu, Nian's hometown in east
China's Anhui Province, also became known to nearly every Chinese
as the "hometown of roasted seeds."
</P>
<P>
During the first stage of China's reform and opening-up
process, the private economy was considered only as a useful
supplement to the public sector.
</P>
<P>
Some people, still clinging to the dream of all "eating from
the big rice pot," were jealous of Nian. On his part, Nian found
it difficult to move forward. In the last 10 years, Nian was fined
several times. He said his unsatisfying experience resulted from
his poor management abilities and the overall environment which
had a bias against the private economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ups and Downs of China's "King of Roasted Seeds" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But things have changed. In due time, the Chinese government
has attached bigger importance to the private sector implementing
a policy of "encouraging and guiding the development of private
and self-employed businesses."
</P>
<P>
China now has 960,000 private firms employing 13.5 million
laborers with an annual output of 390 billion yuan. In some
coastal provinces with higher economic growth rates, the private
economy contributes more than 10 percent to the local GDP (gross
domestic product).
</P>
<P>
In 1995, after 10 years of silence and learning, Nian decided
to stage a comeback. To his satisfaction and surprise, his "Shazi"
roasted seeds still attracted lots of consumers.
</P>
<P>
Rather than continuing his former family management style, Nian
set up the Shazi Seeds Co. Ltd and got support from
shareholders. He also established a national marketing network and
developed 20 new varieties of roasted seeds. He even exported 17
tons of roasted seeds to the United States.
</P>
<P>
A production line with an investment of 30 million yuan is also
under construction.
</P>
<P>
More important, Nian employed lawyers and specialists. In the
past, Nian only wrote down his name on contracts, paying no
attention to the terms. But now, he signs contracts only after
consulting with his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
"He (Nian) has improved greatly with regards to both management
and education standards," said Yu Qing, Nian's consultant. "It's
not easy for a 60-year-old man."
</P>
<P>
Yu said that with improvement in the overall environment and
better management, Nian is able to do more.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Adopt New Air Route Management Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Aviation Administration
of China will adopt a new air route control measure for its two
airlines starting at midnight today to reduce flight delays,
according to today's Wenhui Bao.
</P>
<P>
Management through radar will replace former program control
over airlines from Beijing to Shanghai and from Shanghai to
Guangzhou in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The new measure will shorten the spacing between two planes to
75 kilometers, or about five minutes, which is equal to doubling
the air route. It also helped raise the utilization and turnover
rates of civil planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
