<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control over State Tobacco Monopoly System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China has tightened its
management of state-monopolized tobacco marketing by intensifying
its law-enforcement efforts in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It dealt with 34,000 cases involving the use of fake trademarks
for 470,000 cartons of cigarettes, and discovered 37,000 tobacco
smuggling cases and confiscated 72,000 cartons of contraband
cigarettes last year, according to information from a recent
national working meeting held in Taiyuan, capital of north China's
Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
According to the same source, the country also smashed 684
operations for making illegal cigarettes, and confiscated 2,405
cigarette-making machines in addition to raw material and
accessories.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was convened for the purpose of setting
goals for reforming and developing China's tobacco industry,
decided that the priority of this year's tasks is to continue and
improve the present state tobacco monopoly system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
