<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President-elect of Costa Rica Ends North America Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican President-elect
Miguel Angel Rodriguez has wrapped up an official trip aimed at
drumming up investment and trade with the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, Rodriguez met with U.S. President Bill
Clinton, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Commission Jesse Helms, previous senate
majority leader Robert Dole and President of the World Jewish
Congress Edgar Bronfam.
</P>
<P>
During his ten-day tour, Rodriguez requested an increase in
commercial benefits that the Caribbean Basin initiative grants to
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the U.S. Department of State to suppress a
warning notice to North American citizens traveling to Costa Rica,
which was issued after an American was killed in a land dispute.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, Rodriguez met with First Minister of Quebec Lucien
Bouchard and other leaders of the province.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez, a candidate from the Social Christian Unity Party
(PUSC), defeated his rival from the ruling National Liberation
Party, Jose Miguel Corrales, last February.
</P>
<P>
He will take office on May 8 for a four-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
