<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist Temple Gains Sanitary Source of Drinking Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Monks living in the Gumbum
(Ta-erh) Temple, one of the four largest Buddhist temples in
China, used to get drinking water from a small river and a well.
</P>
<P>
Things have changed with the recent completion of a
14-kilometer water line constructed with financial assistance from
the central government.
</P>
<P>
The piping system now supplies 33 square meters of sanitary
water to hundreds of the monks, thousands of local villagers from
seven villages and an increasing number of tourists and pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
The temple is 25 kilometers south of Xining, the capital of
Northwest China's Qinghai Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
