<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Agrees to Cut Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- OPEC oil ministers agreed Tuesday
to cut production by 1.245 million barrels a day from in a bid to
lower global supplies and stabilise falling prices.
</P>
<P>
The output cuts, the first in years, will take effect
Wednesday, said a statement issued at the end of a six-hour
meeting at Vienna-based headquarters of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
"Reflecting their serious desire to stabilize the market in the
interests of all oil producers, OPEC member countries have agreed
to voluntarily cut" production until the end of 1998, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is the sole member of OPEC exempt from the production cuts
accord due to its "exceptional" circumstances, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The cuts will be on the basis of February output by members,
rather than on the official quota levels, it added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 OPEC and non-OPEC countries have announced plans
in the past week to cut output by a total 1.5 million barrels a
day to try to stabilize oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Prices have plunged by up to 40 percent after OPEC agreed at a
meeting in Jakarta in late November to raise the ceiling
production by 10 percent to 27.5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
The slump was also caused by weak demand in Asian countries, a
mild northern hemisphere winter and increased Iraqi exports.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC group consists of Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
