<HEADLINE> China's Per Capita Vegetable Availability Outstrips World Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The availability of vegetables
per person in present-day China is 250 kilograms (kg), exceeding
the world average, according to information from the Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Business at the vegetable markets in Beijing is just as brisk
as that in southern Chinese cities with a great variety ranging
from fresh tomatoes and cucumbers to green hyacinth beans.
</P>
<P>
Vegetables had been in short supply in some Chinese cities
because of temperature changes in a vast area which ranges from
temperate and subtropical zones to tropical zones. A decade ago
radishes, Chinese cabbage and potatoes dominated meals in the
homes of China's northern urbanites during the winter.
</P>
<P>
The central government launched a program across China in 1988
to improve and increase the supply of non-staple food in the
country's urban areas.
</P>
<P>
During the last decade, the state allocated 3.03 billion yuan
for the construction of vegetable markets. Up to now, five major
open-market centers have been built in eastern and southern
Chinese areas for growing vegetables to supply northern Chinese
areas when fresh vegetables become scarce in winter.
</P>
<P>
More farmers in north China also have turned to greenhouses to
grow vegetables in the winter to supply urban markets.
</P>
<P>
The vegetable-growing area in China amounts to 740,000
hectares, and the total vegetable output was 313 million tons last
year. That represents an increase of 90.4 percent in growing area
and 102.4 percent rise in output, according to comparable figures
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The vegetable market in China has a plentiful supply with a
great variety. Statistics show that about 50 kinds of vegetables
are being traded on the market in many major Chinese cities each
day. For medium- and small-size cities, the number is 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
