<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Equity Inflow to Philippines Surges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign equity inflows into the
Philippines grew by 23.85 percent to 11.4 billion pesos (308
million U.S. dollars) during the first two months of 1998, from
9.2 billion pesos (249 million dollars) recorded for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The increased foreign equity inflows further boosted
investments registered with the Philippine Board of Investments
and the total amount of investments surged by an impressive 65
percent to 79.09 billion pesos (2.1 billion dollars) during the
same period from its year-ago level of 47.88 billion pesos (1.3
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The data from the board said on Tuesday that the increase in
foreign equity inflows were partly due to the appreciation of the
peso against the dollar, which reached as high as 46 pesos to one
dollar but has now scaled down to 37 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Records showed that energy-related projects topped the list of
major investments, accounting for 37.21 billion pesos (1 billion
dollars) of the total volume registered.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong emerged as the top foreign investor in the
Philippines during the period with 6.42 billion pesos (174 million
dollars) in equity infusion, followed by Japan with 2 billion
pesos (54 million dollars) and Virgin islands with 1.9 billion
pesos (51 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
