<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Stone Age Relics Discovered in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered three sites of Stone Age relics in Yunxian County in
central China's Hubei Province. Pieces of picks, axes and
stone-sharpening tools were unearthed.
</P>
<P>
The find increases the evidence that the Hanjiang River Valley
is one of the major birthplaces of Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
The 1,500 kilometer Hanjiang River is the longest tributary of
the Yangtze River, China's longest.
</P>
<P>
Yang Honglin, associate professor from Hubei Province's Yunyang
Normal School, pointed out that the middle and upper reaches of
the Hanjiang River, with a great number of archeological
discoveries, can be called an "early man corridor" where people
lived 200,000-to-1.5 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
Yang said Chinese archeologists have discovered a series of
cultural relics in the Hanjiang River Valley since the
mid-1970s. These discoveries include: four fossilized teeth of
early men dating 800,000-to-one million years ago, in addition to
stone tools and more than 20 kinds of fossilized animals; seven
teeth of early men dating 400,000 years ago; and fossilized living
beings and stone tools.
</P>
<P>
Yang said the most important discovery was in 1989 and 1990
when fossilized head bones were unearthed in Yunxian County, in
addition to 44 stone tools and 10 species of fossilized animals.
</P>
<P>
Rice, tools made of stone and bone, and daily life utensils
dating 5,000-to-7,000 years ago have also been unearthed in the
region in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
