<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Picture Curved in Song Dynasty on Exhibit in Changsha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A curved stone picture, 33.6
meters long and 1.5 meters high, is being exhibited in Changsha,
capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The curved stone picture is made of a computer-controlled
burin, a prehistoric chisel-like tool. The picture is a copy of
"Riverside Scenes on Qingming Festival," a well-known Chinese
painting made in the Song Dynasty (960 to 1279 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
The picture is believed to be a representative work of
introduction of Chinese custom.
</P>
<P>
The picture shows crowds of people, a prosperous ancient
capital, running carts on streets, and boats on rivers.
</P>
<P>
With the computer-controlled machine developed by Changsha
Liming Computer Research Institute, the stone picture was
completed in several months.
</P>
<P>
The real picture is housed in the Palace Museum in
Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
