<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Republic-EU Trade Deficit Goes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's trade deficit
with the European Union has started to diminish since 1996, Czech
Trade and Industry Minister Karel Kuhnl said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit with the EU countries fell to 100.08 billion
Korun (3.05 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997 from 123.3 billion Korun
(3.73 billion dollars) in 1996, said Kuhnl.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's exports to the EU amounted to 430.5
billion korun (13 billion dollars) and imports came to 531.3
billion korun (16.1 billion dollars) in 1997, up 24.3 percent and
13.2 percent respectively over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Germany replaced the former Soviet Union as the country's
largest trade partner, and Slovakia came second, according to the
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
