<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia, Bosnia Agree to Set Up Cooperation Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Croatia and Bosnia have agreed to
establish a cooperation council to guarantee regular high-level
contacts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Croatian Foreign Minister Mate
Granic and his Bosnian counterpart Jadranko Prlic.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Croatian president and the president
of the three-member Presidency of the Republic of Bosnia will meet
each other at least twice a year while the two foreign ministers
will consult regularly.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very important agreement," Granic said after the
signing in Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would certainly be conducive to the improvement
of the Bosnian-Croatian ties, said Prlic.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Bosnian foreign minister also held talks Monday
with Croatian President Franjo Tudjman on issues such as the
return of refugees, admission to the European Union and North
Atlantic Treaty Organization, the establishment of Croat-Bosnian
ties, Bosnian use of the Croatian port of Ploce and the
construction of highways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
