<HEADLINE> Latin American Economical News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from the Latin American countries over the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- the Argentine petroleum company YPF has
bought 29.95 percent of the "Manguinhos" Brazilian Refinery stocks
for 27 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The refinery processes 13 thousand barrels of oil per day and
owns 60 service stations in Rio de Janeiro and other plants
within the state of San Pablo.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's mining industry is expected to reduce
investment to 2.229 billion U.S. dollars from 2.762 billion
dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- A total of 139 oil wells will be drilled
in Colombia this year to increase crude oil production, said the
Colombian Petroleum Company.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRAZILIA -- Brazil exported 11,800 tons in January and February
this year, a 35 percent increase from that of the same period last
year, said the Brazilian Association of Pork Exporters.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico registered a deficit of nearly 6 billion
dollars in trade with the European Union in 1997, said the
National Bank of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's exports to EU reached 4.024 billion dollars in 1997
while imports from the EU amounted to 9.928 billion dollars,
resulting in a deficit of 5.904 billion dollars. 
</P>
