<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Vegetable Basket Project" Enriches Chinese People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The "Vegetable Basket Project,"
launched by the Chinese government in 1988 has produced bountiful
results, according to statistics provided by the Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
China's annual output of vegetables now exceeds 250 billion
yuan (30.01 billion U.S. dollars), second only to that of grain
and higher than forestry and fishery.
</P>
<P>
The acreage cultivated for vegetables in China reached 740,000
hectares in 1997, with output at 313 million kilograms (kg). The
per capita output stood at 250 kg, higher than the world's average.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, China set up a group of vegetable
seed-breeding centers and seedling bases in addition to five
commodity vegetable centers in south China's Hainan Province, the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and the eastern Chinese provinces
of Jiangsu and Anhui.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in major Chinese cities such as Beijing,
Shanghai and Tianjin, more than 50 kinds of vegetables are sold
every day, and in medium- and small-size cities, the number
exceeds 30.
</P>
<P>
Planting vegetables has become an effective way for farmers to
escape poverty. The number of counties with 6,000 hectares planted
in vegetables exceeds 500, three times the figure a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
In northeast China's Liaoning Province, the average annual
income for 1 million rural families engaged in the cultivation of
vegetables has surpassed 5,600 yuan (674.6 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Grows Between Brazil and Andean Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The trade between Brazil
and the Andean countries grew 21 percent in 1997 from that of the
previous year, with a surplus of 1.016 billion U.S. dollars in
favor of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's exports to the Andean group totaled 2.529 billion
dollars and imports reached 1.513 billion dollars, said Brazil's
trade authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Andean group consists Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's trade volume with Venezuela and Bolivia increased 50
percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
Brazil exported 1.488 billion dollars of goods to the two
countries and imported from them 1.5 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
