<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Volcanic Hot Springs Attract Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Tengchong County in southwest
China's Yunnan Province has been making a promising tourist
industry out of its volcanic hot springs.
</P>
<P>
The county, bordering Myanmar, has preserved some extinct
volcanos of the Cenozoic Era. As a result, it now has more than 80
steam and hot springs, 11 with temperatures as high as 90 degrees
Celsius, higher than the local water boiling point.
</P>
<P>
Of all the springs, the nine-square-kilometer "hot sea" is the
best-known. It has countless holes, gushing steam and hot water.
</P>
<P>
Another one is the "big boiling pot" spring, with a diameter of
6.12 meters and a stable temperature of 96-to-97 degrees
Celsius. A head of cattle reportedly fell into the spring and
cooked in about 10 minutes. Local women boil eggs atop on steam
holes and sell them to tourists.
</P>
<P>
The county has received nearly 500,000 visitors over the past
five years. And local hospitals also use the hot springs to treat
certain diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Tornadoes Destroy 635 Homes, Kill One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Rare March tornadoes have
destroyed an estimated 635 homes in southern Minnesota of the
United States, killing a 6-year-old boy and injuring at least 38
people.
</P>
<P>
Over two hours Sunday, the tornadoes cut a swath of destruction
through nine communities, pulverizing much of St. Peter and
Comfrey, The Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Governor Arne Carlson cut short a trip to Washington so he
could tour the damaged areas, and sent National Guard troops to
help.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Emergency Management Agency made available some of
the trailer houses used last year to house victims of disastrous
flooding along the Minnesota-North Dakota state line.
</P>
<P>
St. Peter, a town of 10,000 residents, was hardest hit Sunday.
State officials said more than 500 homes were destroyed and 1,700
others were damaged.
</P>
<P>
People who were able shoveled glass and other debris into the
streets Monday and plows and front-end loaders deposited the
wreckage in state trucks.
</P>
<P>
Gustavus Adolphus College, where most students were away on
spring break, was a disaster. Many campus buildings were damaged,
including the chapel, which lost its 137-foot spire. A campus
parking lot looked like a junkyard, with about 50 cars tossed
around and their windows blown out.
</P>
<P>
In Comfrey, a town of about 550 people, the fire station, the
city liquor store, a cafe and a church were all demolished, and
the school had heavy damage. Fifty homes were destroyed and gas
leaks forced residents to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
Comfrey was without water, sewer or electricity, and power
company crews weren't expected to reach the town until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was only the seventh time Minnesota has recorded tornadoes
in March. Craig Edwards of the National Weather Service said
unseasonably warm weather produced by El Nino seemed the most
logical explanation for Sunday's tornadoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian National Wrestling Team to Leave for U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian Wrestling Federation
Monday announced that the Iranian national wrestling team would
leave Tuesday morning for an international free-style wrestling
tournament to be held in Stillwater, Oklahoma of the United States.
</P>
<P>
