<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges House to Lower Drunk Driving Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Monday urged the House of Representatives to lower the
blood-alcohol content standard for drunken driving to 0.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on the House to follow the Senate's example,
which voted by a 62-32 margin March 4 to urge states to set the
0.08 percent level.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 15 states have that standard while 35 states use a
more lenient 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"It is my fervent hope that the majority of the House will join
the large bipartisan majority in the Senate, and send me
legislation that will make our streets safe, our drivers sober and
our laws more sensible," Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The president, who is touring Africa, also said the .08
provision could save as many as 600 lives a year.
</P>
<P>
Donna Shalala, the health and human services secretary,
speaking at an event Monday at the White House, urged the House to
bring the bill with the .08 provision to the floor before
recessing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
