<HEADLINE> U.S. Disappointed over Failure of Ross's Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
expressed its disappointment over failure of a mission by its
special envoy Dennis Ross for reviving the deadlocked peace
process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We have been unable to bridge the gaps on the hard questions,"
State Department spokesman James Robin told reporters. He said
the peace process "is in dire straits."
</P>
<P>
Ross has asked Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to
back Washington's proposal that Israel withdraw from 13 percent of
the West Bank in several stages within 12 weeks with each stage
accompanied by Palestinian security gestures.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli leader, however, said he did not expect a
last-minute breakthrough. He said only Israel will decide its
security needs and from that the scope of a long-delayed pullback.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the United States would stop mediation for the
Middle East peace process because of Ross's failure, Rubin said
Washington had not made a decision to walk away from its role as
Middle East mediator, although that remained "an option."
</P>
<P>
Ross ended a diplomatic offensive in the region on a bleak note
on Monday, citing diminishing hopes for the Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Ross was expected back in Washington on Tuesday,
when he would report to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Washington had worked hard to develop negotiating
proposals that could be accepted by Israelis and Palestinians
but "in the absence of decisions by those leaders to bridge the
gaps themselves, there isn't that much the United States can
do."  
</P>
</TEXT>
