<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Reviews Report on Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said Monday he will take the next few days to review an
intelligence report that reportedly contends Cuba poses little
threat to America's national security.
</P>
<P>
"My understanding is that it is completed, and it should arrive
at my desk today and then I'll have an opportunity to review it in
the next several days and then make comment on it," Cohen told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks at the Pentagon at a photo session when
meeting with Romanian Defense Minister Constantin Ionescu.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the Defense Intelligence Agency,
concludes that Cuba poses no significant threat to U.S. national
security, the Miami Herald reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Pentagon intelligence portrays Cuba's
Revolutionary Armed Forces as a severely diminished military and
downplays the risks posed by chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believe that such a report may lead to a gradual
lift of the embargo against Cuba imposed by the U.S. 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, some legislators in the Congress oppose lessening
sanctions against the Caribbean nation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U.S. administration decided to soften
the sanctions by allowing humanitarian airplanes to fly directly
to Cuba and Cubans in the U.S. to mail cash to their relatives in
Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
