<HEADLINE> Madcow Disease Forecast to Dwindle Significantly by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 30 (Xinhua) - Britain's Agriculture Ministry said
Monday that the epidemic of madcow disease in the country's cattle
herds will decline to an insignificant level by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a progress report on the fight against the
disease that the number of cases was continuing to fall sharply.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the number of suspected madcow disease
reached its peak in 1992 to stand at 44,846, with the confirmed
cases at 36,682.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of suspected and confirmed cases fell to
10,701 and 8,016 respectively in 1996 and dropped further down to
5,547 and 3,410 respectively in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that thousands of cattle which have been
exposed to infection with the disease has been slaughtered in an
effort to get the European Union (EU) ban for UK beef exports to
be lifted.
</P>
<P>
The EU beef export ban was introduced two years ago when
scientists found evidence that madcow disease, or Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), could be transmitted to humans
who ate infected meat.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that these measures "will accelerate the
decline of the disease, but are not expected to advance the date
of final eradication, and forecasts that the BSE epidemic will
decline to an insignificant level by the year 2001...remain
unchanged". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
