<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt Seeks Final Solution to Religious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
vowed to take measures to deal with the fundamentalists who
incited riots in the country which enjoys stability over the past
three decades.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Home Affairs Ali Ameir Mohamed on Monday told
reporters that strategies to curb commotion are being worked out.
</P>
<P>
"We are serious to find a lasting solution to the problem, "
he said, adding that measures to stop the recurrence of religious
riots at the Mwembechai Mosque might be presented to the cabinet
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday afternoon, hundreds of rioters near the mosque
burned two government vehicles and attacked offices of the
Tanzanian ruling party Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) here. They have
also looted shops and used loudspeakers to summon their
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Two people were killed during the riot, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
One three-year-old girl, Semeni Shabani, was stoned and burnt
to death by a group of fundamentalists who emerged from the
mosque. The bereaved mother, whose right arm and face are badly
burnt, said in the hospital bed of the Muhimbili Medical Center
(MMC).
</P>
<P>
"I escaped into a CCM office to take shelter, with my baby on
back, but the group arrived in several minutes. They rained
stones on the roof of the office, poured petrol into the room and
set fire on it," she said. Earlier, one of the stones hit her
child on head.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the mother, four other seriously injured people
have been admitted to the hospital, said MMC's public relations
officer, McDonald Mwaijande.
</P>
<P>
Police and the Field Force Unit used tear gases to disperse
the mob who were armed with clubs, stones, and helped to restore
the social order till 7:45 pm.
</P>
<P>
The riot is suspected to have a political nature and
foreigners may have laid hand in it, the minister point out.
</P>
<P>
They wanted to disrupt the peace and tranquility the east
African country has been enjoying since its independence in 1963,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Such kind of things have never taken place until recently.
There must be a force behind it and we will deal with the
situation accordingly," he said.
</P>
<P>
The riot, the second in seven weeks, is reported to have
happened after the police banned a meeting of the Committee of
Moslem Women last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen Moslem women, acquitted of charges in the Mwembechai
riot case last month, have recently demanded an apology from the
government, claiming they were maltreated in custody by the
police.
</P>
<P>
The women were held during a riot near the Mwembechai Mosque
in mid-February, in which two people, including a Moslem school
teacher, were killed, and more than 200 hundred people were
arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
