<HEADLINE> Jordanian-U.S. Ties Excellent: Jordan's PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Salam Majali said here Monday that Jordan's relations with the
United States are excellent, Jordan's official news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from the U.S., Majali said King Hussein's
current visit to the U.S. "achieved excellent results regarding the
confirmation of the American economic and military support to
Jordan as well as the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Majali accompanied King Hussein to the U.S. on the visit which
started from March 12, but he came back home Monday evening while
the king's visit is still continuing.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans expressed their appreciation to His Majesty
King Hussein's stands" on the peace process and trusted the
"wisdom and smartness" of the king and attached importance to his
advices and experiences, said Majali.
</P>
<P>
"The American administration pledged (to the king) to offer 225
million U.S. dollars aid to Jordan in 1999," said Majali.
</P>
<P>
For the special role Jordan plays in the Middle East peace
process, the U.S. provided the kingdom with a total of 1.552
billion dollars aid from 1990 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
The king discussed with the U.S. officials the developments of
the peace process on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks in a bid to
deal with the obstacles hindering the peace process, said Majali
who attended most of the king's the discussions with U.S. leaders.
</P>
<P>
"The American side expressed their view point regarding the
Lebanese-Israeli track and think that it is a step in the
way of solving issues on the other tracks," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the king proposed to President Bill Clinton during
their meeting in Washington on March 19 to open direct political
dialogue with Iraq in order to iron out their differences,
according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans did not show full rejection to conducting a
dialogue with Iraq," Majali said. 
</P>
