<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese Official Visits Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Portugal and Mozambique must find
out a way, through constructive dialogues, to solve problems
arousing from the Cahora Bassa Hydro-Electric Power station
(HCB), a senior Portuguese official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Luis Amado, Portugal's Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs
and Cooperation, who arrived here Monday afternoon, said that the
power project should no doubt serve the development of
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that Portugal and Mozambique can
find out the way to make the HCB, the project jointly constructed
by te two countries, to serve Mozambique in a "unquestionable
way".
</P>
<P>
HCB was jointly built by Mozambique and Portugal in the 70s in
northwestern Mozambique. The 1,400 km transmission lines link the
power dam with South Africa's Appolo substation, from there power
is transmitted to the Mozambican capital city Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Its high-voltage towers, destroyed during the 16-year long
civil war in Mozambique, were repaired by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
But the dispute over the power price between Portugal and
South Africa, the biggest foreign buyer of the power from HCB,
stopped the power station from supplying electricity to South
Africa, and hence no power to Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi had expressed the
hope last Friday that people in southern Mozambique could be
electrified with power from HCB, despite of the price dispute.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the Portuguese official who would stay in the
country for a five-day visit, could help find out a way for the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi said that he was shocked to find that Portugal had
unilaterally raised the power price for customers in northern and
central Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980331.0296 </DOCNO>
