<HEADLINE> Liberian Refugees Begin to Return from Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The first group of nearly 393
Liberian refugees of old age Monday began to return home from
neighboring Guinea, with the aid of the United Nations refugee
agency.
</P>
<P>
The cheerful refugees left their camp some 1,100 km from the
Guinea capital of Conakry, with provided kitchen utensils, mats,
blankets and agricultural tools, according to the British
Broadcasting Corporation monitored here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 refugees fled from Liberia to Guinea since
the civil war started in late 1989.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) is
spearheading the repatriation of these refugees, who are all
volunteers to go home.
</P>
<P>
An impressive ceremony was held to mark the beginning of the
repatriation of the Liberian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the ceremony include Liberian defense and
internal affairs ministers as well Guinean internal affairs
minister, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian officials, in their speeches, expressed absolute
gratitude to the Guinean government and people for their
hospitality.
</P>
<P>
They also ensured the international community that the
government would help the returned refugees to settle down well.
</P>
</TEXT>
