<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Inaugurates Water Pipe Plant in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Transport Secretary Rodney
Slater Monday inaugurated a water pipe plant in Gaborone, capital of
Botswana, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The plant belongs to Owens Corning of Botswana, a joint venture
between the U.S.and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
The plant is to manufacture glass fiber pipes to link the Gaborone
Reservoir to the terminal of Botswana's 360 kilometer north-south
water carrier.
</P>
<P>
Slater, who is with U.S. President Bill Clinton for a visit in
Botswana, said: "The venture is a good example of how we can support
the broad goals of the president's (Africa trade) initiative."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. mission is touring Africa to advocate its U.S.-Africa
Growth and Opportunity Act, which is basically aimed at replacing aid
to Africa with trade and opening the African market for American
goods.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. exports to Africa support 100,000 American jobs and in
Africa, projects like this create new jobs, spur growth and improve
the quality of life," Slater said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. bill was welcomed by Botswanan President Ketumile Masire.
In a speech to welcome Clinton on Sunday, Masire described the bill as
"America's solemn bond to Africa."
</P>
<P>
However, the legislation encountered harsh criticism in South
Africa. South African President Nelson Mandela said the bill was
"unacceptable" to his country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his wife Hillary are at a game reserve in the northern
town of Kasane to enjoy safari. They will return to Gaborone Tuesday
en route to Senegal, the last leg of their six-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
The Clintons have visited Ghana, Uganda, Rwanda and South Africa.
</P>
