<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More U.N. Procurement from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- China hopes that the
United Nations will increase peace-keeping procurement from
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Sheng Guofang, Deputy Permanent Representative to the U.N. made
the point at the Special Committee on Peace-Keeping Operations
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that U.N. procurement is unfairly over
concentrated to a small number of countries have not been changed
and rather aggravated.
</P>
<P>
While Asian developing countries are taking a bigger and bigger
share in the world economy, U.N. procurement at those countries
accounted for no more than one percent of its total in 1997, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He further took China as an example. China, the world's tenth
largest trading country with a GDP representing the world's 2.5
percent, accounted for only 0.04 percent of U.N. procurement.
</P>
<P>
What's more, he said, "this tiny amount has all gone to
payment of printing cost, which means that the U.N. did not spend
a nickel in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
developing countries from other regions are in similar plight,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Sheng said China hoped that peace-keeping procurement, part of
U.N. procurement, will be conducted in a more transparent manner
and the U.N. will formulate more preferential policies to
developing countries in this regard. 
</P>
